<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Conditions on Make-up of Peace Force in East Timor, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said Monday that Indonesia could place no conditions
on the make-up of the international peace force expected to be
sent to East Timor soon.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency of Ansa, Dini, who was
speaking on the sidelines of a meeting of European Union foreign
ministers in Brussels, said the EU was preparing to place a
"temporary" embargo on the supply of arms to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He said that "Indonesia cannot put any conditions on the
composition of the force," echoing a similar statement issued at
around the same time by United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
The remarks by Dini and Annan appeared to be a response to
calls in the Indonesian parliament for Jakarta to oppose the
inclusion of Australia, New Zealand, the United States and
Portugal in the force.
</P>
<P>
Dini added that "Indonesia is fully responsible for the
atrocities" committed in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian parliament's defense committee said these
countries were not neutral and it would be better if the force
were made up of troops from Indonesia's Pacific neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The East Timor has been under violence since the August 30
referendum on independence, in which 78 percent of East Timorese
voted to break with Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The vote sparked a wave of violence by pro-Indonesian militia's
who went on the rampage, killing and attacking anyone they saw as
having voted for independence.
</P>
<P>
Of the EU nations, Italy, along with Britain and France, has
said it is ready to send soldiers to East Timor as part of a UN
force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
