<HEADLINE> N.Irish Unionists Lash out at Police Reform Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's leading
Protestant party on Monday rejected the proposals to reform the
British province's police force and said it would draw up
alternative ideas.
</P>
<P>
After a three-hour meeting, the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP)
described the report by an independent commission headed by Chris
Patten as "deeply flawed and objectionable", the Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read by party leader David Trimble, the
executive said "it must not be accepted as the way forward for
policing in Northern Ireland".
</P>
<P>
Trimble said a six-person working party was being set up by the
UUP to produce "alternative proposals" to the Patten report.
</P>
<P>
Trimble also brushed off reports that his leadership position
was in trouble, saying it was rock-solid.
</P>
<P>
Earlier a leading UUP parliamentarian had called for him to
resign but Trimble told reporters there had been no challenges to
his position during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Patten report recommended a sweeping overhaul of the mainly
Protestant Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC) in a bid to attract
recruitment from the nationalist Catholic community.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said his party "considers that the recommendations to
remove symbols associated with the United Kingdom are designed to
undermine the identification of the RUC as the Northern Ireland
element of British policing".
</P>
<P>
The council also said "the recommendations create a channel for
the involvement of terrorist organisations in policing". 
</P>
</TEXT>
