<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends to Protect Civilians in Armed Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Monday that the responsibility for the
protection of civilians in armed conflict cannot be transferred to
others and the United Nations is the only international
organization with the reach and authority to fulfil this task.
</P>
<P>
In his report on the Protection of Civilians in armed Conflict,
Annan said "Despite the adoption over the past 50 years of the
main conventions of International Humanitarian and Human Rights
Law, hardly a day goes by where we are not presented with evidence
of the intimidation, brutalization, torture and killing of
helpless civilians in situation of armed conflict."
</P>
<P>
Annan made nine recommendations as being of particular
importance to the Security Council for its consideration regarding
the protection of civilians in armed conflict. They are
</P>
<P>
-- Take steps to strengthen the Organization's capacity to plan
and deploy rapidly.
</P>
<P>
-- Establish a permanent technical review mechanism of United
Nations and regional sanctions to ascertain the probable impact of
sanctions on civilians.
</P>
<P>
-- Impose arms embargoes in situations where civilians and
protected persons are targeted by the parties to the conflict and
urge member States to enforce these embargoes in their own
national jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
-- Consider deployment in certain cases of a preventive
peacekeeping operation, or of another preventive monitoring
presence.
</P>
<P>
-- Make greater use of targeted sanctions to deter and contain
those who commit egregious violations of international
humanitarian and human rights law, as well as those parties to
conflicts which continually defy the resolutions of the Council.
</P>
<P>
-- Deploy international military observers to monitor the
situation in camps for internally displaced persons and refugees,
and if such elements are found, deploy regional or international
military forces that are prepared to take effective measures to
compel disarmament.
</P>
<P>
-- Underscore in its resolutions the imperative for civilian
populations to have unimpeded access to humanitarian assistance,
and insist that failure to comply will result in the imposition of
targeted sanctions.
</P>
<P>
-- Ensure that whenever required, peacekeeping and peace
enforcement operations are authorised and equipped to control or
close down hate media assets.
</P>
<P>
-- In the face of massive and ongoing abuses, consider the
imposition of appropriate enforcement action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
