<HEADLINE> U.S. Condemns Bombing in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States
condemned the bombing that took place in Moscow that have resulted
in dozens of deaths, U.S. Stated Department spokesman James Rubin
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We extend our condolences to the families of the victims who
have suffered loss and injury," Rubin told a regular news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"These recent events only serve to strengthen our commitment to
the government of Russia and to the people of our two countries to
work more effectively together to combat these kind of heinous
crimes," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Early on Monday, at least 34 people were killed in a blast
which tore through an apartment block in southern Moscow. Another
explosion killed 94 people last week also in the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
"Russia is conducting an investigation. We stand ready to
assist that investigation and will be discussing possible
assistance with the Russian authorities shortly," the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
