<HEADLINE> Alatas to Continue Talks with U.N. on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Talks on the
deployment of a U.N.-sponsored force for East Timor between
Indonesia and the United Nations will continue Tuesday as they
have to further discuss a number of issues.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas made the statement as he
emerged from an one-hour meeting with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and the president of the Security Council here Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The questions on the table include the composition and the
nature of the force, the role of the Indonesian military in the
next stage and others, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia would like to see this security cooperation, the
sending of a U.N. force realized as soon as possible...with no
conditionalities attached," the Minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said he came "open-minded" as to which countries will
participate in the mission.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to the countries themselves to consider whether their
presence would or would not exacerbate the situation (in East
Timor) rather than improve the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas put the deployment of such a force as a new question as
the May 5 agreement between Indonesia, Portugal and the United
Nations provides that the U.N. mandated peace-keeping force goes
to East Timor only after the ballot result begins to be
implemented after November.
</P>
<P>
He said he doesn't think all detailed technical questions can
be solved in one short talking, while expressing his willingness
to stay here "as long as it takes" for them to be solved.
</P>
<P>
Alatas arrived in New York Monday in the wake of President B.J.
Habibie's announcement Sunday that Indonesia accepted a
U.N-sponsored international force to restore security and order in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Violence has taken place in the former Portuguese colony
integrated by Indonesia in 1976 following the August 30
U.N.-organized ballot on its future, which showed voters' support
for independence instead of special autonomy within Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was meeting Monday afternoon on the
dispatch of the force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
