<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Hard Hit by Widespread Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Widespread floods caused by a
 week of torrential rains have rendered 9,195 people homeless in
upper east and northern regions of Ghana, the Ghana News Agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
An accompanying cholera outbreak has killed at least 48 people
in these regions, Upper East Coordinator of the National Disaster
Management Organization, Thomas Abilla, told President Jerry
Rawlings during a tour of the affected areas over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Abilla said that as a result of the floods, three dams have
burst banks, three roads have been completely destroyed and one
bridge has collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The collapsed bridge has stranded several trucks transporting
imported goods from Ghana's ports to landlocked Burkina Faso and
Mali, witnesses were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Abilla said 530 acres of farm crops have also been destroyed,
while 687 houses (mostly thatched) have totally collapsed from the
floods which have affected 179 communities.
</P>
<P>
"The opening of the spillways of the Bagre Dam in Burkina Faso
over the past week has further aggravated the situation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The disaster management official said that the loss caused by
the floods could run into millions of cedis (one U.S. dollar
equals some 2,540 cedis).
</P>
<P>
He added that the victims are currently being housed in schools
and called for emergency assistance to relocate them to enable
school children to resume their classes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
