<HEADLINE> Kenya Shares Drop as Foreign Capital Outflows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 13 (Xinhua) --The stocks in Kenya dropped
marginally Monday as grim prospects for the fragile economy
prompted foreign investors to flee the embattled bourse, brokers
said.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE) 20-share index fell by 0.1
percent or 2.65 points to close at 2434.24, the lowest level since
December 10, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the stocks here plunged to a record low of
2,466.88 points.
</P>
<P>
Brokers here said the index, which has slumped 16 percent this
year, would fall further as poor interim results combined with
Kenya's economic mess caused both local and foreign investors to
abandon the market.
</P>
<P>
The brokers also urged the Kenyan government to give a tangible
plan for economic recovery to restore investors' confidence and
stop further falls. 
</P>
