<HEADLINE> Albright Recommends to Ease Trade with DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright is recommending that President Bill Clinton
ease restrictions on trade in response to a pledge of freezing
missile test by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK), the State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Albright was notified on Sunday by chief U.S. negotiator
Charles Kartman that the DPRK had taken the pledge, State
Department spokesman said. As a result Albright "is prepared to
recommend to the president that we move ahead with easing
restrictions on the trade of non-sensitive goods and investment,
certain financial transactions and transportation restrictions,"
Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
But there will be no easing of a ban on the sale of U.S.
weapons and missile-related technology as well as on U.S. foreign
and economic aid, except humanitarian assistance, Rubin said.
