<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Reiterates Call for Full Israeli Pullout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa on Monday reiterated his country's demand for full
Israeli pullout from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the closing session of the two-day
Arab foreign ministers' meeting here, al-Sharaa said full Israeli
withdrawal from Golan is Syria's ultimate goal through peace talks
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Our position has been in place for several years and our
demands are fair and irrevocable," he said.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations between Syria and Israel came to a halt in
early 1996 due to disputes over the return of Golan Heights
captured by Israel from Syria in the 1967 Arab-Israeli War.
</P>
<P>
After the election of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in May,
the two neighbors have expressed willingness to resume the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa described the relations between Damascus and Cairo as
very strong, saying "No ties between two other Arab countries are
stronger than those between Syria and Egypt."
</P>
<P>
The Syrian foreign minister cited constant consultations
between the two countries on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Reports have said that the Egyptian-Syrian relations soured
after Syrian President Hafez al-Assad snubbed Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak's call for an Arab summit aimed at forging a common
stance on the Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting between Mubarak and Saudi
Foreign Minister Saud al-Faisal on Monday, Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa said there is no plan for a meeting between
Egyptian and Syrian presidents in the near future. 
</P>
