<HEADLINE> OPEC President in Saudi Arabia for Talks on Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 13 (Xinhua) -- President of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) Youcef
Yousfi arrived on Monday in the Saudi Red Sea port city of Jeddah
for coordination ahead of an OPEC meeting due in Vienna later this
month.
</P>
<P>
Yousfi, who is also Algeria's Energy and Mines Minister, is
expected to hold talks with his Saudi counterpart Ali al-N'aimi on
the implementation of the OPEC output reduction agreement signed
in March.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, OPEC members began to cut their daily
production by 1.7 million barrels on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's biggest oil producer and exporter,
had reiterated its pledge to maintain the cutbacks in Venezuela
late last month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yousfi assured during his visits to the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and Kuwait, the first two legs of his present Gulf
tour, that OPEC members will adhere to the agreement until March
2000.
</P>
<P>
He said there was a consensus among OPEC members to maintain
production cuts until next March as high crude stockpiles were
not expected to disappear before then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
