<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are brief
economic news from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Member states of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
have been warned that their heavy commitments to developing
petroleum production capabilities may trespass upon government
expenditures on education, health, social activities and other
services.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Dubai in its quarterly report has estimated that
four oil-rich Gulf states, namely, Kuwait, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will need to spend about 125
billion U.S. dollars till 2010 to develop 129 billion barrels of
petroleum reserves to meet anticipated demand during the said
period.
</P>
<P>
The Bank predicted that the four Gulf states will seek other
alternatives to increase oil production, including loans or
granting ownership rights of petroleum to foreign companies, the
Arabic-language Al Hayat daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Algerian Minister of Energy and Mines Youcef
Yousfi, who is the current chairman of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), said that oil prices at
present are satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
Yousfi, who arrived in Abu Dhabi Sunday on a Gulf tour,
expressed his belief that OPEC members would decide in its coming
meeting on September 22 in Vienna to maintain their commitment to
the oil production cuts agreed upon in March until March 2000.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by OPEC members to boost oil prices by reducing
production have been well-paid with the standard price of Brent
crude oil fetching 23.5 U.S.dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- The 23rd regular session of the Council of Central
Bank Governors and Arab Petroleum Establishments began its works
in Muscat, Oman, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Participants would work out a coherent and flexible economic
and banking policy that covers the diverse aspects of life, the
Arabic-language Al Hayat daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The total value of Egyptian exports during the first
six months of 1999 has reached about 5.69 billion Egyptian pounds
(1.67 billion U.S. dollars), as compared to 5.387 billion pounds
(1.58 billion dollars) during the corresponding period of 1998, up
by 5.6 percent, Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed
Gowaili was quoted Monday by the Al Ahram daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total value of imports during the period stood
at about 27.946 million Egyptian pounds (8.2 million dollars), as
compared to about 26.985 million pounds (7.9 million dollars)
during the corresponding period of 1998, up by 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- An exhibition of leather and footwear will be
held in Sharjah, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), from September 18
to 21.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 exhibitors from 22 countries and regions will
take part in the exhibition, which will be patronized by the
International Leather Council, the Arab Union for Leather
Industries and Sharjah Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The participating countries include Egypt, Syria, Sudan,
Tunisia, China, Germany, Greece, Italy, South Africa, Spain,
Switzerland and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
