<HEADLINE> Food Reaches Town in Hands of S. Leone Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Food supplied by the United
Nations and other international agencies has for the first time
reached the areas controlled by the rebels in northern Sierra
Leone over the weekend since the signing of the Lome agreement in
early July.
</P>
<P>
A convoy of 60 trucks carrying over 1,000 tons of food has
arrived in Makeni, a rebel stronghold in the region, and
distribution work had already begun, reports reaching here quoted
a U.N. official as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The convoy is expected to relieve the grave food shortage
tending to starve local residents and the rebels as well.
</P>
<P>
Since signing the Lome peace deal with the Sierra Leonean
government, the rebels have been surviving by stealing and looting
from local people, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
It was one of the main demands that food and medicine be sent
to them immediately when some of the rebels staged a
hostage-taking drama, in which several dozens of international aid
workers were held for a few days last month.
</P>
<P>
Innocent people are dying everyday in the rebel-controlled
regions due to malnutrition and medicine shortage, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
This has become an insatiable factor for the smooth
implementation of the Lome peace agreement, hardly earned after a
nearly one decade of civil war in this west African country.
</P>
