<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Resume in Tanzanian Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A new round of talks to
end Burundi's civil war started Monday in Tanzania's northern town
Arusha without the presence of the international peace mediator
Julius Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
Judge Mark Bomani, representative of Nyerere, told Xinhua over
telephone from Arusha that delegates will pick up issues left over
during their last meeting in the town two months ago, such as
resettlement of refugees, peace, economic reconstruction, among
others.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, Tanzania's founding president and a veteran African
statesman, is in London with an undisclosed illness. But he is
expected to return to Tanzania to join in the talks soon after
medical treatment, Bomani said.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks have made little progress since they began in June
last year because of mistrust between different factions over a
conflict in which more than 150,000 people have died since October
1993.
</P>
<P>
Bomani has urged delegates to work seriously so that the
negotiations for final peace deal could speed up.
</P>
<P>
Burundian government officials say this session is crucial in
the wake of a rebel attack on capital Bujumbura last month, in
which 38 civilians and 20 rebels were killed.
</P>
<P>
However, the rebels say they are fighting the Tutsi-dominated
army to defend the rights of the country's Hutu majority.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier General Hashim Mbita, spokesman for Nyerere, told
reporters in Arusha Monday that "violence can never help to find
an answer."
</P>
<P>
"We wish those involved in violence to know that Burundians
have suffered enough," reports reaching here quoted Mbita as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"The ongoing Arusha peace talks give a hope for Burundi to end
violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
The one-week talks bring together opposition and rebel groups
and the government of President Pierre Buyoya, who took power in a
military coup in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, a rebel group CNDD-FDD, which insisted on fighting in
Burundi, has not been invited to the talks, Bomani said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
