<HEADLINE> Chile's Aninat Named IMF Deputy Managing Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, the
Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
announced Monday the appointment of Eduardo Aninat, currently the
Finance Minister of Chile, as Deputy Managing Director of the IMF
to a five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Aninat will succeed Alassane D. Ouattara, who left the IMF at
the end of his appointment July 31, 1999, to pursue his political
career, the IMF said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"I have been impressed for many years with Dr. Aninat's grasp
of the issues affecting the international economy, as well as with
his energy and clarity of purpose in discharging his key
responsibilities as the Minister of Finance of one of the most
successful economies in the world," Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
"His first-hand knowledge of the challenges of policy-making,
particularly in a period of international financial volatility
which has also affected Chile, will be an invaluable asset for the
IMF in its role as economic policy advisor to its member
governments," Camdessus added.
</P>
<P>
Aninat, who has an M.A. and Ph.D. in economics from Harvard
University, has been the Finance Minister of Chile since March
1994. He was the Chairman of the Board of Governors of the IMF and
the World Bank in 1995-96, and served three years as a member of
the Development Committee of the World Bank and the IMF,
representing the constituency of six countries: Chile, Argentina,
Bolivia, Peru, Uruguay and Paraguay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
