<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Tea Prices Pick Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's tea prices rose by an
 average of five to eight U.S. cents per kilogram at the weekly
tea auction as the quality of tea improved, sources from the
African Tea Brokers said at southeastern port city of Mombasa
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Best Pekoe Ones were sold at 2.48 to 2.62 U.S. dollars per
kilogram from last week's 2.42 to 2.50 dollars while Best Pekoes
Fannings rose to 2.40-2.47 dollars per kilo from 2.35-2.42
dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, traders there said that the quantity on offer at the
auction was down almost by half compared with the figures over the
past few weeks, due to the dry weather for the tea-growing areas
in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
They also noted the dry weather had led to better quality tea,
saying that the tea quantity might go on declining as dry
conditions continue.
</P>
<P>
African Tea Brokers said traders from Egypt, Sudan, Yemen and
other Middle East countries had showed more interest and there
were also some orders from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecasts indicate that there will be no much rainfall
for October in Kenya. This will be conducive to the tea
plantations producing better quality tea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
