<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Sets Agricultural Production Targets For </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is targeting to
double its staple maize production to 3.1 million tons in the next
five years in a bid to improve the country's food security, Lands
and Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the country's Policy Strategies for Stimulating
Agriculture Production and Food Security for the 1999/2000 farming
season and beyond, Kangai said that increased maize production
would not only ensure adequate local supply, but also allow
exports to progressively increase from 350,000 tons to 550,000
tons annually.
</P>
<P>
"The primary policy objective for Zimbabwe, as far as maize
production is concerned, is producing white maize to satisfy
national human consumption, nutrition and food security
requirements," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
In the next five years, he said, wheat production is expected
to increase from 320,000 tons to 400,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that cotton production, estimated at 300,000
tons for this year, should increase to 320,000 tons during the
next season and surpass 400,000 tons over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
On tobacco, he said that production of flue-cured tobacco
should not drop below 200 million kilograms, while the country
should aim to produce up to 20 million kg of burley tobacco from
the current seven million. Tobacco is one of Zimbabwe's single
largest foreign currency earners.
</P>
<P>
"The strategy for increased production will take into account
the need to create a competitive environment for investment to
expand acreages and establishment of infrastructure," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Immediate attention needs to be put into improving yields in
the communal areas and ensuring food security, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said the policy document looked at each commodity covering
the current situation, constraints affecting production and
strategies to increase production.
</P>
<P>
Coordinated efforts in research, extension, training and
utilization could lead to better technologies and increase
production, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
