<HEADLINE> OECD Secretary-General Positive About China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The secretary-general of the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD),
Donald Johnston, gave here Monday a positive evaluation of his
visit to China last week.
</P>
<P>
He told the press that he was impressed by the determination of
the Chinese government to continue the country's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that it is in the interests of the 29 member
countries of the OECD to accompany China "in its increasing
integration with the global economy."
</P>
<P>
The OECD will help China make an evaluation of the advantages
and implications of a wider opening trade policy for China's
domestic development, and prepare for a common guide of direct
foreign investment in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based organization will also carry out on a regular
basis dialogue with the Bank of China on macro-economic analysis
and reform of China's financial sector, and cooperate in
developing "knowledge economy" in China, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said the OECD's member countries understand China's
intention to join the World Trade Organization (WTO), although his
organization does not directly join talks of the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Johnston visited China from September 7 to 12 at the invitation
of the Chinese government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
