<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestine Launch Final-status Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EREZ CHECKPOINT (ISRAEL), September 13 (Xinhua) -- Israel and
Palestine officially launched the final-status talks in a ceremony
held here Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Executive Committee of the Palestinian
Liberation Organization Mahmoud Abbas, also known as Abu Mazan,
led the Palestinian delegation to the ceremony, while the
Israeli delegation was led by Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Special Coordinator of the Middle East Peace Talks Dennis
Ross, European Union's Special Envoy to the Middle East Miguel
Moratinos and representatives from the United Nations, Russia,
China, Japan, Norway, Egypt, Jordan and Finland were also present
on the occation.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony marked the very good beginning for both sides to
build mutual trust which could be conducive to help procceed the
negotiations. Levy, who arrived at the site ahead of Abbas, warmly
greeted the later at the gate of the meeting room.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, both Abbas and Levy spoke about their
commitments to reaching a final accord that will end the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict and enable Palestinians and Israelis
to be separated and live in peace.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who spoke first, said that if the two sides can not reach
a framework accord within five months, then it will be very
difficult for both sides to strike a comprehensive peace treaty
by the next September as stipulated by the newly signed peace deal
in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"The Middle East peace process has reached the last storey of
the building of peace and it is also a very arduous task facing
us. We hope the two sides to make all efforts to reach a
comprehensive agreement for realizing the lasting peace in the
region," Levy said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Levy also repeated the policy of the Israeli
government for the final-status talks, saying that the Israel's
policies on Jerusalem, borders and settlements remain the same as
before.
</P>
<P>
In return, Abbas voiced his appreciation that both sides signed
new peace deal in Egypt and the cooperative relationship between
Arafat and Barak, saying such relationships laid a solid
foundation for achieving lasting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the Palestinian policy towards Jerusalem,
borders, the settlements and the Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
"We are aspired to live within the 1967 borders as an
independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital and
to achieve a just solution to the Palestinian refugee problem in
accordance with the U.N. Resolution 194 and to dismantle the
Israeli settlements in accordance with the U.N. resolution 465,"
Abbas said.
</P>
<P>
Under the newly-signed peace agreement, the two sides are to
negotiate most thorny issues such as the status of the Palestinian
entity, borders, the status of Jerusalem, the fate of Palestinian
refugees, and the future of Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
The reopening of the final-status talks here was set by the new
peace deal, a revised Wye River Accord, signed by Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak last
Sunday in Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm El Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
The new peace deal stipulates that the Israelis and
Palestinians should work out a statement of principles on final
peace deal in five months and the deadline for the agreement is
September 13, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Israel has already transferred 7 percent of the West Bank land
to the Palestinians and released 200 Palestinian prisoners last
Thursday as underlined in the Sharm El Sheikh Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
Israel has to carry out another two troop withdrawals from the
West Bank in November and January next year, besides releasing
another 150 Palestinian prisoners on October 8 as stipulated by
the deal.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the southern "safe passage" between Gaza Strip and
the West Bank is to opened on October 1, while construction
of the Gaza seaport to commerce on the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Assembly Concludes 53rd Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly (GA) session concluded Monday after its plenary
conference unanimously adopted a resolution on the culture of
peace, which involves all countries and regions in the pursuit of
peace.
</P>
<P>
The session was chaired by the outgoing GA president, Didier
Opertti of Uruguay, who assumed the presidence at the beginning of
the closing GA session in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, entitled "Declaration and Program of Action on
a Culture of Peace," said that the GA recognizes that peace is not
only the absence of conflict, but requires a positive, dynamic
participatory process where dialogue is encouraged and conflicts
are solved in a spirit of mutual understanding and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The GA also recognizes that "the end of the cold war has
widened possibilities for strengthening a culture of peace," and
expresses "deep concern about the persistence and proliferation of
violence and conflict in various parts of the world," the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution recognizes "the important role that the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
continues to play in the promotion of a culture of peace."
</P>
<P>
In introducing the draft, Anwarul Chowdhury, Bangladesh's
permanent representative to the United Nations, said, "I sense
that a great interest in this document beyond the world of the
United Nations, this has a far-reaching implication in its
implementation."
</P>
<P>
"I believe this document is unique in more than one way: it is
a universal document in the real sense," he said. "This document
is action-oriented and encourage actions at all levels, that is,
the level of the individuals, the community, the nation, the
region -- all at the global or international levels."
</P>
<P>
The document also brings together various actors who pursuit
the culture of peace; they include states, international
organizations, civil societies, community leaders, parents,
teachers, professors, artists, journalists and humanitarian
workers, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In a way, all the people from all walks of life and all sorts
of background can contribute in the implementation," he said.
</P>
<P>
On November 9, 1988, the GA president, upon the conclusion of a
debate on the culture of peace, mandated the Bangladeshi
delegation to coordinate the consultations in a bid to produce a
draft resolution.
</P>
<P>
The consultation concluded on September 2 this year after a
consensus text was reached. The draft underlined the importance of
the U.N. Charter and the primary responsibility of the United
Nations in the maintenance of world peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The resolution says, "The culture of peace is a set of values,
attitudes, traditional and modes of behavior and ways of life"
based on respect for life, ending of violence and promotion and
practice of non-violence through education, dialogue and
cooperation, full respect of the principles of sovereignty,
territorial integrity and political independence of States and
non-intervention in matters which are essentially within the
domestic jurisdiction of any State.
</P>
<P>
The culture of peace also covers such fields of eradicating
poverty and illiteracy and reducing inequalities within and among
nations, promoting sustainable economic and social development,
eliminating all forms of discrimination against women, and
increasing transparency and accountability in governance.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was inspired by a GA resolution, which was
adopted on January 18, 1988 to proclaim the year 2000 as the
International Year for the Culture of Peace.
</P>
<P>
The celebration of the International Year was led by the United
Nation Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
In his closing speech, Opertti said, "It was doubtless the
conflict in Kosovo, which, owing to its magnitude and
consequences, was the most important international political event
of the years."
</P>
<P>
He said that the conflicts in the world, technological progress
and the unbalanced economic development, organized crime,
terrorism and environmental degradation are major challenges
facing mankind in the next century.
</P>
<P>
During its 53rd session, the General Assembly considered a
total of 170 items at 107 plenary meetings and nine informal
meetings. It adopted 309 resolutions -- 248 of them by consensus
-- and 130 decisions, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
