<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Painstaking Task By Qi Deliang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Exactly six years after the
signing of the Oslo Accord for Palestinian self-rule, Israel and
the Palestinians officially launched their final-status talks at
the Erez Checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Witnessing up and downs, breakthroughs and setbacks in the
peace process, the whole world is cheered up again for the smooth
reopening of the final-status talks as mandated by the new peace
deal signed by Palestinian leader Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak last Sunday in the Egyptian Red Sea resort of
Sharm El Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
The deal asks the two sides to work out a statement of
principles on the final peace deal in five months and sets the
deadline for reaching the agreement on September 13, 2000.
</P>
<P>
No doubt, the new peace deal has charted the course towards a
historic permanent peace accord between the Israelis and
Palestinians and in reality, the negotiating teams are facing a
daunting task.
</P>
<P>
Within five months, by February 15, the two sides have to
present the outlines of an accord on the nature and borders of the
Palestinian entity, the status of Jerusalem, the future of the
Jewish settlements on occupied land in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip and the fate of over 3 million Palestinian refugees,
pending a full peace accord to be reached by September 2000.
</P>
<P>
Although many Israelis and Palestinians want to settle all
those thorny issues once for all, the two sides still remain far
apart even till now over the above mentioned issues.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to establish an independent sovereign
state in all of the West Bank and Gaza Strip with East Jerusalem
as the capital, while demanding the return of over 3 million
Palestinian refugees and dismantling the Jewish settlements
unwilling to remain under Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Israel wants to annex parts of the West Bank and Gaza Strip to
keep most of the 20,000 settlers under Israeli rule. It also says
it will never relinquish parts of Jerusalem and will not permit
the return of refugees to areas under its control.
</P>
<P>
Monday's reopening of the final-status talks is viewed as a
historical event for both Israelis and the Palestinians. But to
solve all the remaining thorny issues will be a painstaking task
for both sides to deal with. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-13 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
