<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GA President on Challenges Facing Mankind in Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The outgoing president
of the 53rd General Assembly (GA) session, Didier Opertti of
Uruguay, Monday said peace, technological progress,
globalizations, drug trafficking and organized crimes are major
challenges facing mankind in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as the president was delivering a closing
speech at the plenary session of the GA, which began Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The president, also foreign minister of Uruguay, made the
statement as the world is poised to greet a new century, "a
century which offers a glimpse of prospects both promising and
disturbing, one marked by the existence of deep-seated
contradictions which are the major challenges humankind must
meet."
</P>
<P>
He sees these contradictions in three main areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
First, "the world is continuing to move towards the full
realization of individual freedoms and the democratization of
national societies and international society," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Although much remains to be done, it is surely true that never
until now have the ideals of democracy and freedom been so widely
realized," he said.
</P>
<P>
"During the 12 months since this Assembly began its fifty-third
session, violence has dominated and affected the lives of people
in many parts of the world, often taking away those lives, and so
creating a legacy of fear and bitterness in people's hearts," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In Europe, in Africa and in Asia, old and new conflicts
continue to require the international community's attention and
call with increasing urgency for the adoption of attitudes and
gestures of solidarity rooted in tolerance," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The second major contradictions relate to technological
progress, the revolution in communications and transport and the
extraordinary expansion of scientific knowledge, which has enabled
humankind to reach unprecedented levels of material development,"
he said. "However, the benefits from such progress are not
distributed equitably among the various segments of humanity."
</P>
<P>
"The process of globalization does not mitigate this
contradiction," he said. "On the contrary, it is a generally
accepted conclusion that the dramatic acceleration of the
globalization process that has been taking place these past few
years, resulted from the opening of markets and the liberalization
and modernization of trade, does not prevent the intensification
of the social differences and individual societies," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The third major contradiction resulted from the fact that,
while many societies have achieved a high degree of social
integration, with high levels of knowledge, culture and creative
activity, these same societies appear to be extremely vulnerable
to such dangers as drug trafficking, organized crime, terrorism
and environmental degradation," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the GA's 53rd session, "intensive negotiations were held
in determining the format and content of" the Millennium Summit,
which is scheduled to be held during the 55th GA session beginning
in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
The summit "will provide a unique opportunity to consider the
role of the United Nations in the next century," he said.
</P>
<P>
During its 53rd session, which ends Monday, the General
Assembly considered a total of 170 items at 170 plenary meetings
and nine informal meetings. It adopted 309 resolutions -- 248 of
them by consensus -- and 130 decisions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly is the main deliberative organ. It is
composed of representatives of all Member States, each of which
has one vote.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the functions and power of the General
Assembly include discussing and making recommendations on the
principles of cooperation in the maintenance of international
peace and security, and receiving and considering the report form
the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The GA's regular session usually begins each year in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non Arrival of African Leaders to AIDS Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the World
Health Organization (WHO) have expressed disappointment at the
non-arrival of various heads of state to the on-going 11th
International Conference on AIDS and STDS (sexually transmitted
diseases) in Africa (ICASA).
</P>
<P>
The disappointments were expressed at a joint press conference
in Lusaka Monday by Executive Director of the Joint United Nations
Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), Peter Piot and Vice-President of the
World Bank African region, Calliso Madavo and WHO regional
director for Africa Ebrahim Samba.
</P>
<P>
Taking the lead in showing disappointment on the non attendance
of the heads of state who had showed willingness to attend, Samba
said he had not yet heard any reason why all failed to attend the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The names of the heads of state and their countries were not
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
"I'm disappointed at the fact that heads of state are not with
us here," the WHO official said. "They may have their reasons for
not turning up the meeting."
</P>
<P>
The same sentiments were expressed by Piot from UNAIDS, who
said there was need to put HIV/AIDS issue on the national agenda
wherever heads of state or government gather so that they can
discuss and commit themselves to the fight of the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said about two thirds of the AIDS cases in the
world are registered in African countries.
</P>
<P>
Referring to would-be steps to be taken, Piot pointed out that
there will be nothing achieved in the fight against the disease.
Hence, there is the need to have a political commitment from
governments.
</P>
<P>
In its statement released earlier at the conference, the World
Bank said that national governments must take the lead in fighting
AIDS, because there are things that only governments can do, or
make it possible for others to do.
</P>
<P>
Without these things, the struggle cannot succeed, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
