<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Launches Spy Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain revealed Monday it had
suspected "traitor granny" Melita Norwood of spying for the Soviet
Union for half a century but had never interviewed her in order
not to jeopardize other investigations.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw, under pressure to reveal the facts
about Norwood and a second Soviet spy unmasked by Moscow defector
Vasili Mitrokhin, said he first learned of her activities in
December 1998, BBC reported.
</P>
<P>
Straw has ordered an investigation into MI5's handling of the
spy scandal.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Straw said Norwood, an 87-year-old grandmother
at the center of a British spy scandal, had been given clearance
in 1945 to do secret work despite doubts about her communist
associations.
</P>
<P>
But four years later there were "new concerns" and she lost her
access to secrets about the development of Britain's atomic bomb
in 1949. She was vetted in 1951 and again in 1962 but refused
clearance.
</P>
<P>
In 1965 an investigation concluded she had been a spy in the
1940s but came up with no usable evidence and the then Labor Home
Secretary Frank Soskice was informed.
</P>
<P>
But Britain's MI5 counterespionage agency decided not to
interview her "because that would have revealed the Service's
knowledge which was relevant to other sensitive investigations
then underway."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, the home secretary met the head of MI5, Stephen
Lander, amid growing concern that the intelligence service took no
action against former Soviet spies after it was made aware of
their existence.
</P>
<P>
Straw's statement came as two former Labor MPs were also named
as Soviet agents.
</P>
<P>
Tom Driberg and Raymond Fletcher, who are both now dead, are
the latest Cold War spies to be named from files brought to the UK
by Russian dissident Vasili Mitrokhin.
</P>
<P>
Driberg, who was MP for Barking, East London, was known by the
codename of Lepage, while Fletcher, then MP for Ilkeston,
Derbyshire, was codenamed Peter, according to the files Mitrokhin
smuggled into the UK in 1992.
</P>
<P>
A former policeman, John Symonds, has also admitted he was a
"Romeo agent," sleeping with women from foreign embassies to gain
secrets for the KGB in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office said a decision not to prosecute would have
been made not by the home secretary, but by the police and Crown
Prosecution Service -- and was probably taken because of the
amount of time that had elapsed.
</P>
<P>
The revelations came to light when a BBC team was researching
the forthcoming documentary "The Spying Game."
</P>
<P>
"The Spying Game" will be broadcast on BBC Two on September 19.
It will include an exclusive interview with KGB defector Vasili
Mitrokhin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
