<HEADLINE> Egyptian Police Officials Censured for Failure to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian police disciplinary
board censured two top police officers Monday for dereliction of
duty over an attack on President Hosni Mubarak, the Interior
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The board ordered that 14 other Port Said police officers stand
trial for negligence in connection with the assassination attempt
on Mubarak on September 6, the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The officers were accused of "negligence in providing
protection" for Mubarak during a visit to Port Said, 180
kilometers northeast of Cairo, at the northern end of the Suez
Canal.
</P>
<P>
Port Said Security Director Maj. Gen. Hassan Abdel Motteleb
Othman Jebril and Director of State Security Investigation Maj.
Gen. Abdullah Nasr will be deprived of promotion and retire next
year, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The 14 other officers, including Criminal Investigation
Director Brig. Mohammed Sallem Shalan, will stand trial in a
special police court "for negligence of duty in protecting the
president," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
A knife-wielding man attacked and slightly injured Mubarak as
his motorcade passed through the city. The man was shot dead by
Mubarak's guards. Police say he was deranged.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak blamed the attack on lax security. He sacked the
intelligence chief and ordered a security review.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said an unspecified number of junior policemen and
informers will also go on trial for negligence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
