<HEADLINE> Greek Banks Announce Measures to Assist Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Greek banks Monday announced a
package of measures aimed to assist the victims of last Tuesday's
earthquake which hit northwestern Athens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting of the union's board, Theodore
Karatzas, chairman of Greek banks' union, said that these measures
included supporting citizens hit by the earthquake through the
extension of mortgage, personal and consumer loans payment
timetables by six to nine months, extending all due interest
payments on business loans by six to nine months, lowering
personal, consumer and business loans' interest rates by two
percentage points until December 31, 2000 and freezing all
enforced actions for a period of six months.
</P>
<P>
Greek banks would cover the costs of separate reconstruction
projects totaling more than 3 billion drachmas (about 1 million
U.S. dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
Karatzas said that all Cypriot banks operating in Greece would
contribute in the efforts of the reconstruction of the regions
that were mostly damaged.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday's earthquake measuring 5.9 on the Richter scale
had an epicenter in the Mount Parnitha region, some 20 kilometers
northwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
So far, 122 people have died in the earthquake, which is
estimated to cost Greece 100 billion drachmas (about 333 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
