<HEADLINE> Carol Bellamy Re-Appointed as UNICEF Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Carol Bellamy, current
executive director of the United Nations Children's Fund, was
re-appointed Monday by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan as head
of the agency.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said at Monday's noon briefing that
Bellamy's re-appointment will take effect on May 1, 2000, at the
conclusion of her present term.
</P>
<P>
Outlining some of her goals for a second five-year term,
Bellamy said, "Although we have many successes behind us, we have
many challenges before us. The scourge of HIV/AIDS, the damaging
consequences of conflict, and the asphyxiating effect of poverty
and debt are all growing. It is our responsibility -- for the sake
of children everywhere -- to overcome them."
</P>
<P>
In her coming term, Bellamy will devote the UNICEF to promoting
a new "global agenda for children" -- recruiting leaders in
government, civil society, academia, the media and the private
sector to commit themselves to making sure that all children
survive; that they grow up healthy in a protected environment;
that they obtain a quality basic education; and that fewer women
die during childbirth or from preventable causes.
</P>
<P>
Since her original appointment in May 1995, Bellamy has worked
to increase visibility and support for the millions of children
around the world whose lives are battered by war. She has traveled
to the war-devastated countries of Angola, Sierra Leone, Albania,
and Afghanistan, among others, to underscore every child's right
to basic protection, whatever his or her circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF operates in more than 160 countries worldwide,
helping governments and civil society provide for and protect the
health, education and general well-being of children and women. It
has an annual operating budget of roughly 1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
