<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Says "One Country, Two Systems" Is The Best Way To Unify China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The "one country, two systems
" policy is the most realistic and feasible way for China to be
unified, Lu Ping, the former director of the State Council's Hong
Kong and Macao Affairs Office, told Xinhua recently.
</P>
<P>
Since his retirement five days after the return of Hong Kong to
the motherland on July 1, 1997, Lu has been concerned with the
unification of the nation, in which he played such an active role
during his years in office.
</P>
<P>
He started that work in 1978 and witnessed the whole process of
forming the "one country, two systems" policy and putting it into
practice. It was initially designed for the Taiwan issue but was
successfully implemented to solve the Hong Kong issue.
</P>
<P>
Lu explains that the policy maintains the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the nation on the one hand while taking
into consideration the interests of parties concerned on the other
and shows a high-degree of flexibility.
</P>
<P>
"One China" is both the basis and the core and allows flexible
measures to be adopted in accordance with the real situation, he
says.
</P>
<P>
After unification under this policy, Taiwan will not have to
change its social or economic system and the Taiwanese will not
have to change their way of life. Compared with Hong Kong and
Macao, Taiwan will have more flexible policies, including keeping
its own armed forces. It can best guarantee Taiwanese compatriots'
hope of maintaining the present situation and safeguarding their
interests, Lu says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Because of the long-term separation and the obstructions put up
by Taiwan authorities, some Taiwanese compatriots still can not
fully understand the "one country, two systems" concept and still
have doubts about it, but this doesn't matter, he says, as long as
they agree on the "one China" principle they will come to agree on
the "one country, two systems" idea after seeing it in Hong Kong
and Macao.
</P>
<P>
He says that when it was first suggested as a way to solve the
Hong Kong issue, many people in Hong Kong also had doubts, but
when they saw the policy fully implemented, more and more people
began to agree with and support it.
</P>
<P>
The policy is in line with the nation's interests and is not
simply for any single party or any single people, he says, and
Taiwanese compatriots will ultimately come to understand the
sincerity of the Central Government in implementing the "one
country, two systems" policy through greater understanding and
communications.
</P>
<P>
Lu says that the reunification of the motherland is an
unavoidable historical trend and that any remarks like Lee Teng-
hui's "two states" to divide the motherland will certainly be
opposed by the Chinese, including Taiwanese compatriots.
</P>
<P>
The "one country, two systems" policy is the country's basic
policy but the mainland has not said that it will give up the use
of non-peaceful means to unify the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Unifying the motherland and revitalizing the nation are the
life-long pursuits of Lu's generation, and also the will of the
Chinese people. Lu says he is confident that their hopes will be
realized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
