<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Angolans Killed in Rebel's Ambush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Seven civilians in a truck
were killed on a highway near northern Malanje at last weekend
during an ambush launched by the Angolan rebels on a civil
vehicle, a military source said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Land Rover truck is the sixth car ambushed in the same
section of highway in less than two months, which had killed over
30 and injured about a hundred, according to the unidentified
military source.
</P>
<P>
During the attack, six passengers and one driver were shot
dead while another passenger Teresa Pedro Rebeca became the only
survivor in the incident.
</P>
<P>
According to Rebeca, the rebels of the National Union for Total
 Independence of Angola (UNITA) irrigated the bodies of the
victims with gasoline and then burned them.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, UNITA rebels continued to mine the roads with
access to fields and mounted a series of ambushes on the principal
highways, in a bid to impede the provision for the suffered in
Malanje, said the source.
</P>
<P>
It is also reported that four civilians were killed and another
six injured during an attack launched almost simultaneously by the
UNITA rebels against a village called Cateque, only nine
kilometers away from the central fortress Bocoio, in the coastal
Benguela Province.
</P>
<P>
During the assault, 54 houses were reportedly burned and all
properties were robbed by the rebels. Rebel's activities will
deprive local residents of their provisions, seeds and domestic
animals, the source said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
