<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Urged to Help Release Lebanese Journalist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese independent group
Monday urged French President Jacques Chirac to intervene for the
release of a Lebanese journalist arrested recently by Israel on
suspicion of dealing with Lebanese military group Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's Follow-up Committee for Supporting Lebanese Detained
in Israeli Prison said in a statement that it has submitted a
memorandum to Chirac seeking his pressure on Israel to release
Kozet Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim, who works at Alliwaa daily newspaper in Beirut, was
arrested early this month by Israeli troops from her house in the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
She was reported to have suffered barbaric physical and
psychological torturing which made the Israeli troops admit her
to the hospital inside the zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israeli troops out of the country.
</P>
<P>
About 130 Lebanese have been detained without trial in Khiam
prison inside the border enclave for collaborating with
Hezbollah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
