<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Reconciliation Fostered Between Iraq, Other </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A new mood of reconciliation
between Iraq and other Arab states has taken hold, the Arab League
(AL) secretary-general said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the two-day Arab foreign ministers'
meeting here, Esmat Abdel-Meguid said that while differences
remain between Iraq and the Gulf Arab states, discussions have
been "very civilized."
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf chaired the
meeting, marking the first time Iraq had taken the league's chair
since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. The seat rotates annually
among the 22 members.
</P>
<P>
"The Gulf crisis is a problem, but at least we have now a
beginning of trying to find an acceptable solution," Abdel-Meguid
said of the legacy of Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The six Arab states of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
censured Iraq on Saturday for its defiance of the United Nations
Security Council resolutions and insisted that Iraq admit the
invasion violated international law.
</P>
<P>
Asked why Iraq did not pursue reconciliation to the point of
making such an admission, al-Sahhaf said the GCC statement was an
example of public diplomacy, not real diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a matter of who will apologize to others. It is a
matter of common sense," al-Sahhaf said. "Each GCC member has its
own policy on Iraq but the common approach is gradually growing
positive."
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq trades with five GCC states - Bahrain, Oman,
Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates, except
Kuwait. The volume of Iraqi-Saudi trade stood at 157 million
U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said the league is to send a delegation to inspect
an Israeli exhibit at Disney World's Epcot Center in Orlando,
Florida of the United States to see if it depicts Jerusalem as
Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
He said the chairman of Walt Disney Co., Michael Eisner, had
called him and invited such a delegation. Previously the company
had refused access to a team from the United Arab Emirates, which
threatened a boycott of Disney products last week.
</P>
<P>
Eisner was "very apologetic and regretful. He was very keen not
to cause any harm to Arab countries or Jerusalem or the peace
process," Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Sunday that Arab
states would not accept the representation of Jerusalem as the
capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the coming Israeli-Palestinian peace talks were to
settle the status of East Jerusalem, which Israel captured in the
1967 Arab-Israeli War and which the Palestinians regard as their
future capital.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot accept anything that would predetermine something
that has to be determined through negotiations," Moussa said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GA Considers Draft Resolution on Culture of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly Monday began a plenary session to consider a draft
resolution on the culture of peace, which involves all countries
and regions in pursuit of peace.
</P>
<P>
The session, also the concluding meeting of the 53rd General
Assembly, was chaired by the outgoing GA president, Didier Opertti
of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
In introducing the draft, Anwarul Chowdhury, Bangladesh's
permanent representative to the United Nations, said, "I sense
that a great interest in this document beyond the world of the
United Nations, this has a far-reaching implication in its
implementation."
</P>
<P>
"I believe this document is unique in more than one way: it is
a universal document in the real sense," he said. "This document
is action-oriented and encourages actions at all levels, that is,
the level of the individuals, the community, the nation, the
region -- all at the global or international levels."
</P>
<P>
The document also brings together various actors who pursuit
the culture of peace; they include states, international
organizations, civil societies, community leaders, parents,
teachers, professors, artists, journalists and humanitarian
workers, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In a way, all the people from all walks of life and all sorts
of background can contribute in the implementation," he said.
</P>
<P>
On November 9, 1988, the GA president, upon the conclusion of a
debate on the culture of peace, mandated the Bangladeshi
delegation to coordinate the consultations in a bid to produce a
draft resolution.
</P>
<P>
The consultation concluded on September 2 this year after a
consensus text was reached. The draft underlined the importance of
the U.N. Charter and the primary responsibility of the United
Nations in the maintenance of world peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The draft says, "The culture of peace is a set of values,
attitudes, traditional modes of behavior and ways of life" based
on respect for life, ending of violence and promotion and practice
of non-violence through education, dialogue and cooperation, full
respect for the principles of sovereignty, territorial integrity
and political independence of states and non-intervention in
matters which are essentially within the domestic jurisdiction of
any state."
</P>
<P>
The culture of peace also covers such fields of eradicating
poverty and illiteracy and reducing inequalities within and among
nations, promoting sustainable economic and social development,
eliminating all forms of discrimination against women, and
increasing transparency and accountability in governance.
</P>
<P>
The draft was inspired by a GA resolution, which was adopted on
January 18, 1988 to proclaim the year 2000 as the International
Year for the Culture of Peace.
</P>
<P>
The celebration of the International Year was led by the
United Nation Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Meet on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council meets Monday afternoon on East Timor, the council
president announced.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting at 4:30 pm EST is expected to discuss
new developments after Indonesia's announcement to accept a
U.N.-sponsored international force in cooperation with the
country's military to restore order and security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's response, announced by Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Sunday, to a U.N. call for such a force was welcomed by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas is expected to arrive in
New York by lunch time Monday to discuss details of the deployment
of the force, said a spokesman for the Indonesian Permanent
Mission to the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Alatas will meet Annan at 3:30 Monday afternoon, U.N. spokesman
Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, leaders of the House of Representatives at a
meeting Monday with President Habibie endorsed the government's
decision to accept the international help, and Habibie said he
fully entrusts the Council to decide which countries would join
the force after consulting with Alatas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
