<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Oil Groups Merge After Elf Chief Surrenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- French oil and chemical giants
Total-Fina and Elf-Aquitaine have agreed to merge on friendly
terms after the former offered to raise its buying price of Elf
stocks by nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The president and executive officer of Elf, Philippe Jaffre,
will quit his post and allow his rival, Total President Thierry
Desmarest, to lead the future group, which will be the world's
fourth largest in the field of oil and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with Desmarest Monday, Jaffre said
that "there is a time to say no and there is a time to yes," and
it is time to say yes after resisting the take-over bid by Total
for more than two months.
</P>
<P>
The reaction of the stock market is believed to have played a
major role in bringing an end to the merger battle, as the market
has played mainly in favor of Total-Fina.
</P>
<P>
The two groups will immediately begin merging their companies
and teams to create the biggest French enterprise with 150,000
employees and 600 billion francs (100 billion U.S. dollars) worth
of stocks listed in stock markets of Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government welcomed the decision after the
announcement was made Monday.
</P>
<P>
Desmarest said that the merger will result in the downsizing of
2,000 jobs in three years, but will not bring about forcible
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
He said that the future merged group will also realize a
combined production figure of 1.5 billion euros (1.575 billion
U.S. dollars) in three years.
</P>
<P>
The administration councils of th two groups met Monday and
proposed to their stock-holders to allow Elf and Total to come
together "in a friendly way, on an equal footing and on the basis
of an ambitious industrial project."
</P>
<P>
Total-Fina, which launched a surprise takeover bid against Elf
on September 5, has agreed to raise its offer by 9.6 percent, or 4
billion francs (667 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
For the rest, the merger conditions will conform with those
presented by Total, including a total integration of the chemical
sector.
</P>
<P>
Elf, which owns a stronger chemical sector that Total, had
proposed to separate the chemicals from the future group and list
them separately in the stock market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
