<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Could U.N. Play Bigger Role? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The 54th session of
the United Nations General Assembly convenes Tuesday with more
country leaders participating, a sign of growing expectation for
the international community at the threshold of a new century.
</P>
<P>
Yongjian Jin, under secretary-general of the U.N., announced
last week that 40 heads of state and 26 heads of government had
been on the list of speakers at the general debate scheduled to
begin a week later. The figures may change more or less, but they
represent a sharp rise over last year's, which stood at 26 and 15
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"It is a clear sign of growing expectation for the United
Nations," Jin said in an interview with Xinhua. The country
leaders want to voice their hope that the international community
will be able to play a more important role in the 21st century, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The developed and developing countries alike seem to believe
that the U.N. has played a unique and indispensable part in
maintaining world peace and security, advancing economic and
social development as well as promoting human rights. It is
commonly realized that no other international or regional
organization could have exerted the same role so far.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. and its NATO allies challenged the U.N.
status early this year by launching an intense bombing of
Yugoslavia in the wake of a "humanitarian crisis" in Kosovo. The
78-day military operation against a sovereign U.N. member state
was not authorized by the Security Council, which shoulders the
primary responsibility for maintaining peace and security
worldwide, a principle enshrined in the United Nations Charter.
</P>
<P>
If the NATO military intervention could set a precedence
without condemnation, will the Security Council manage to exert
its rightful authority in case of crisis? The question needs to be
answered both in theory and practice.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan believes that lessons should
be drawn from the crisis handling. In his report to the new
session of the General Assembly, the U.N. chief stressed that
military intervention should seek the green light from the
Security Council; regional organizations should rather cooperate
with than compete against the U.N. in peace-keeping and peace
making missions; political will and resources from member states
are imperative to securing success.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its NATO allies may cite their new strategic
concept to argue against the conclusion, but it is hard to sell it
to the vast number of developing countries. The new concept,
masterminded by the U.S. and adopted at the April NATO summit in
Washington, allows the regional defense alliance to intervene even
militarily in case of crisis without seeking authorization from
the Security Council. This theory, coupled with the Kosovo
bombing, alerted the world to the danger of marginalizing the U.N.
in the new century.
</P>
<P>
The argument could hardly die down at the new General Assembly
session. But the deteriorating financial situation in the U.N. may
fuel doubts about the U.N.'s capability and efficiency of carrying
out its missions.
</P>
<P>
It is not a secret that the U.N. is deeply troubled by the
serious budgetary deficit over the past few years. The problem
mainly arose from unpaid arrears, which totaled more than 2
billion U.S. dollars in 1998. The U.S. unpaid dues made up
one-third of the total. Even the U.S. allies have protested
against Washington's request for reduced pay rates, but the
Capitol Hill has defied appeals from the White House and foreign
capitals. "The U.N. has been taken hostage by American domestic
politics. If the defiance continues, it will have serious
consequences for the international community," warned a Western
expert on the U.N. affairs.
</P>
<P>
It has been announced that some 160 items have been placed on
the agenda, ranging from preventive diplomacy to sustained
development, from disarmament to drug and crimes, from poverty
eradication to environmental protection. But undoubtedly the
issues of peace and security, economic and social development will
still be the focus.
</P>
<P>
The world leaders need to speak out their desires and concerns,
but it is more important to take actions to back the U.N. if they
really greatly count on it. Only firm political will and
continuous contributions from member states will enable the U.N.
to function better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Diplomacy Aims at Safeguarding National Interests, Promoting World Peace (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin met
with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Auckland, New Zealand, on
September 11 and about two weeks ago, with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin in Bishkek, capital of Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
These two meetings were during a summit of heads of state of
China, Kyrgyzstan, Russia, Kazakhstan and Tajikistan, and the 7th
Informal Leadership Meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation, respectively. Jiang also paid state visits to Italy,
Switzerland, Austria, Mongolia, Thailand, Australia, and New
Zealand this year. Other senior Chinese officials also visited
dozens of countries in the America, Europe, Asia, and Africa.
</P>
<P>
All of these trips are considered important diplomatic
activities by China at the turn of the century and the epitome of
China's active and independent diplomacy of peace since the
founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the founding of New China five decades ago, the
country faced a perilous environment, and half a century later,
relations with major powers have improved remarkably and ties with
neighboring states and other developing countries have seen
progress.
</P>
<P>
As a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council,
China has been playing an increasingly important role in the
international arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Diplomacy Aims at Safeguarding National Interests, Promoting World Peace (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On October 1, 1949, Chairman Mao Zedong proclaimed the founding
of the People's Republic of China, ending a hundred years of
humiliation, and China now has diplomatic relations with more than
160 countries and engages in economic, trade, scientific,
technological, and cultural cooperation with more than 220
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
In the past five decades China has overcome difficult
international problems one by one in part thanks to its flexible
and practical strategies.
</P>
<P>
(Subtitle) Independence -- Standpoint of China's Diplomacy
</P>
<P>
Independence is the basic principle of China's foreign policy.
On the eve of the founding of the new China, Mao Zedong
exstablished the foreign policy of the new socialist China by
first severing all links with the old China's foreign policy, or "
thoroughly cleaning house", as he put it.
</P>
<P>
Even during the China-U.S.S.R. alliance in the 1950s, China
stuck to a principle of independence. In the late 1950s, Sino-
Soviet ties worsened gradually because of the latter's chauvinism,
but China firmly safeguarded the principle, stressing a principle
of equal sovereignty among socialist countries and opposing
chauvinism.
</P>
<P>
In May, 1989, after Deng Xiaoping and Mikhail Gorbachev held
talks in Beijing, the two countries normalized relations on a
basis of mutual respect for independence and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
China has the same attitude towards its relations with the
United States. The U.S. had a hostile attitude towards the People'
s Republic and imposed an embargo to try to stop its development
after the New China was founded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Diplomacy Aims at Safeguarding National Interest, Promoting World Peace (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. government announced that it would continue to
recognize the Kuomintang regime three days after the founding of
New China. Then, on June 25, 1950, the Korean war broke out. The U.
S. brought the war up close to the Chinese border on the Yalu
River and the U.S. 7th Fleet invaded the Taiwan Straits, posing a
serious threat to Chinese sovereignty and national security. To
combat this, the Chinese leaders made a strategic decision to
resist U.S. aggression and help the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea.
</P>
<P>
It was not until the early 1970s that China and the U.S. began
contacts after taking into consideration their respective
strategic interests. Mao Zedong told Edgar Snow, the well-known U.
S. journalist and the old friend of the Chinese people, in 1970,
that he was ready to talk to President Richard Nixon if Nixon
would come to China.
</P>
<P>
After several rounds of diplomatic discussions, Mao and Premier
Zhou Enlai mapped out their "ping pong diplomacy" when the U.S.
government showed its willingness to improve relations. President
Nixon visited China in February of 1972, marking the end of the
stalemate in bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Sino-U.S. relations have had their twists and turns
but the Chinese government has stuck to the principle of
independence and has considered its long-term strategic interests
while respecting the interests of the United States.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese government has made it clear that the
Chinese people can never accept any harm done to national
interests or interference of any kind in China's internal affairs
especially in Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Diplomacy Aims at Safeguarding National interests, Promoting World Peace (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The development of China's independent foreign policy
demonstrates that Chinese leaders have started with the basic
interests of the Chinese people and the people in the rest of the
world and have made decisions in accordance with the right or
wrong of the specific affair and have never bowed their heads to
any external pressure.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign policy also reflects China's increasing
strength and important status in international affairs and a more
mature diplomacy. The independent foreign policy of peace has
withstood the test of time, especially the changing international
situation in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the bi-polar world transformed the basis of
international relations. The late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping put
forward a new strategic policy for China's diplomacy: observe
calmly, stay firmly, cope with the situation cold-headedly, keep a
low profile to lie low and get something done.
</P>
<P>
China continued to steadily develop relations with all
countries based on the Five Principles of Peaceful-Coexistence.
China's firm stand and flexible approaches have allowed the
country to overcome pressure and sanctions imposed by western
countries, thereby creating a favorable environment for economic
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Diplomacy Aims at Safeguarding National Interest, Promoting World Peace (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Maintaining World Peace and Stability for Development of
Humanity
</P>
<P>
Peace and development are the themes of today's world and
seeking peace and stability and promoting cooperation and
development have become the aspirations of all peace-loving
countries and people.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping said in 1985 that peace and development are the
two strategic issues worldwide and development is the core.
</P>
<P>
China, as a socialist country, should pursue a foreign policy
of peace and needs a peaceful international environment to be a
prosperous and strong country. When New China was founded, it
declared that it would strive for independence, democracy, peace,
unification and prosperity, and in diplomacy would make an effort
to safeguard peace in the world.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhou Enlai, in a meeting with an Indian delegation in
1953, put forward the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence for
the first time. The Chinese government then made it clear that
China was willing to establish normal relations with all countries
on the basis of the five principles.
</P>
<P>
From the 1950s to the 1980s, there was no tranquillity in areas
around China and a number of wars broke out like the Korean War,
the war in Viet Nam, Viet Nam's invasion of Cambodia, and the
Soviet Union's invasion of Afghanistan. And, in self-defence,
China had to attack India, the Soviet Union, and Viet Nam during
that period of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
