<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Ends Special Rights for Kosovo Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Kosovo Albanian refugees
seeking asylum in Britain will no longer have special rights to
stay in the country, British Home Secretary Jack Straw said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Straw said that since the withdrawal in June of Serb forces
from Kosovo, the ethnic Albanians were now safe from persecution
in their homeland and their applications to stay in Britain would
be treated "on merit," Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
"Ethnic Albanians are now generally safe from persecution in
Kosovo and this is reflected in the new guidance to immigration
officers which comes into force today," Straw said.
</P>
<P>
"Many who sought refuge in Britain, and elsewhere, have already
returned home," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office said that of the 4,346 Kosovo Albanians who
came to Britain, mainly as part of a U.N. evacuation program, 809
had already returned home voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
It said applications for asylum from Kosovo Albanians were now
likely to be refused.
</P>
<P>
Britain has a backlog of more than 80,000 applicants for asylum
and opposition Conservatives complain the the country had become a
"soft touch" for bogus asylum seekers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
