<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Diplomacy Aims at Safeguarding National  Interests, Promoting World Peace (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was not until the 1990s that the situation with China's
neighbors improved considerably, and, of 15 neighbor countries, 10
signed border agreements with China.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that this is one of the few periods when China has
been able to enjoy better relations with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Deng said in the early 1980s that it was possible that another
major world war would not occur for quite a long time and that
hopefully the world would remain peaceful and he emphasized that
China firmly took the policy of opening up to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
This policy has benefited China's economic growth and
comprehensive strength over the past two decades and has also
contributed to global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, China has been participating in the international
disarmament process and cut its armed forces by 500,000 people in
1997 following the reduction of one million people in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, China signed several dozen
international treaties, including the Comprehensive Nuclear Test
Ban Treaty and the Non-Proliferation Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Several generations of Chinese leaders have believed that the
people of the world and the increase of the forces of peace have
to be relied on to prevent wars.
</P>
<P>
Deng said in 1987 that if the forces for peace in the world
have grown and if the Third World countries get developed a new
world war can be avoided, and, if the Third World countries,
including China, have good development in the first half of the
next century and Europe has good development, the danger of war
can fundamentally be eliminated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
