<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair to Go Back to School to Learn Internet Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said in Cambridge Monday that he was going back to school to
catch up with the computer skills of his wife Cherie and three
children.
</P>
<P>
Blair, in a speech launching a government policy study on how
to boost electronic commerce in Britain, told his audience,
"Here's my confession. In many ways I am the last person to be
making this call to action," Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
"To say the least, I am no expert. To be completely blunt and
honest about it, I watch my children and indeed Cherie surfing the
net and feel a mild, not to say profound, sense of humiliation."
</P>
<P>
Blair said that like many people of his generation, he rarely
used a computer and relied on his staff. "It's a big psychological
barrier to get over," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I've decided it's no use my giving lectures to everyone else,"
he said, announcing he would sign up for a basic computer skills
course.
</P>
<P>
On Monday he started out by ordering flowers for his wife
Cherie, a highly paid barrister, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said Blair, who normally works with a pen and paper
sitting on a sofa rather than at a desk, had yet to acquire a
computer in his office. His course will probably last half a day.
</P>
<P>
Blair announced the appointment of Alex Allan, a top civil
servant who has just returned from a posting as Britain's High
Commissioner to Australia, as the government's "e-envoy" to boost
electronic commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
