<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Refuses to Bring Pinochet Case Under International Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Spanish Foreign Minister Abel
Matutes said Tuesday that he has informed the Chilean government
of Spain's refusal to go to international arbitration in the case
against former Chilean President Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
In an answering letter to his Chilean counterpart Juan Gabriel
Valdes, Matutes stressed Spain's stand that the Pinochet case is a
judicial affair, in which the government has no right to interfere.
</P>
<P>
Valdes wrote to Matutes on September 3, inviting the Spanish
government to "immediately start" formal negotiations so that the
Pinochet case could be solved under international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
In his reply, Matutes confirmed the government's obligation to
accept Chile's request for negotiation in line with international
practice, but stressed "it is negotiation, not arbitration."
</P>
<P>
Although raising no suggestion over the Pinochet case, Matutes
said, the Spanish government has all along made great effort to
maintain its friendly relations with Chile and other Latin
American countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
