<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Guerrilla Leader Released From Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Johnny Adair, a pro-British
guerrilla commander during the Northern Irish conflict, was
released early from prison Tuesday under the Good Friday peace
accord signed in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
Adair, 34, was the former leader of the outlawed loyalist
paramilitary group, the Ulster Freedom Fighters (UFF), in the
Shankill area of west Belfast, and one of the six-man ruling
council of the Ulster Defense Association.
</P>
<P>
Adair was arrested on charges of directing guerrilla activities.
He has served five years of a 16-year jail term in Maze prison.
</P>
<P>
He was the latest of 300 pro-British Protestant and republican
Roman Catholic prisoners to walk free under a controversial early
release scheme.
</P>
<P>
The early release scheme is part of the Good Friday peace
accord, the result of political talks following declaration of
cease-fire by rival extremist groups, who were engaged in violent
campaigns over the future of British rule.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, on a pre-release leave from Maze prison,
Adair was shot at a concert in Botanic Gardens in Belfast. He
blamed the republicans for the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore-Funded Electronic Company Starts Up in  Eastern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Gulted (Suzhou) Electronics Co.
, Ltd., a Singapore-backed high-tech enterprise, began operation
today in Suzhou in China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
It has 36 million U.S. dollars worth of capital from Gul
Technologies Singapore Ltd., and will specialize in printed
circuit boards for medical, telecommunication, and information
technology use and for automobile manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Located in the city's industrial zone, the company covers a 3-
hectare area and has a 24,000-sq.m. workshop that can produce 150,
000 sq.m. of printed circuit boards annually. The project in its
first phase will have 400 employees.
</P>
<P>
Major clients include Ford, Phillips, Solectron, and CISCO. Gul
Technologies Singapore Ltd. was set up in 1988. 
</P>
