<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang: China, NZ Share Extensive, Significant Common Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese
President Jiang Zemin said Tuesday China and New Zealand should
broaden common ground, enhance mutually beneficial cooperation and
work for a brighter future in their relations at the cross of the
centuries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said, "Though different in national conditions,
historical background and cultural tradition, China and New
Zealand share extensive and significant common interests."
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who arrived here Tuesday afternoon following a short
visit in Wellington, made the remarks at a dinner given in his
honor by New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two nations have grown steadily since
the establishment of the diplomatic relations 27 years ago, Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
"Leaders of our two countries have frequently exchanged visits
and had meetings with each other," Jiang said, adding Shipley's
successful visit to China last July played a positive role in
promoting bilateral exchanges and cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Specially mentioning time-honored bilateral friendship, Jiang
said that in the 1920s, Rewi Alley, a famous writer, educator and
social activist of New Zealand, came and worked in China for over
half a century.
</P>
<P>
Citing Alley as a symbol of China-New Zealand friendship, Jiang
noted that Alley made important contributions to China's
revolution and development.
</P>
<P>
Both countries are striving for economic development and better
livelihood for their people, Jiang said, adding, "We are both
actively expanding friendly relations and cooperation with other
countries in the world."
</P>
<P>
Both countries wish to see continued peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific and strengthened regional economic and technological
cooperation in a bid to promote common development, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said, "With strength in different fields, our two
economies are highly complementary. As China gives priority to the
development of agriculture, energy and environmental protection,
it wishes to learn from New Zealand which has an edge in these
fields."
</P>
<P>
There will be a long-term demand for wool, timber, paper pulp
and dairy products in the Chinese market, products that New
Zealand abounds in, Jiang said, adding "there is a good foundation
and prospects for expanded exchanges and cooperation between China
and New Zealand in various fields."
</P>
<P>
Describing the South Pacific region where New Zealand is
situated as an important part of the Asia-Pacific, Jiang said that
given its geographical location and rich natural resources, it
promises tremendous potentials for development.
</P>
<P>
Over the recent years, Jiang said, South Pacific countries have
accelerated their economic development and strengthened
cooperation, and thereby scoring remarkable achievements in the
socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the South Pacific Forum is playing a bigger
role in regional and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
As a major country in the South Pacific, Jiang went on to say,
New Zealand has significant influence in this region, and for
years, it has made vigorous efforts to promote regional peace and
development and has enhanced regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We in China appreciate all these," Jiang stressed.
</P>
<P>
China has all along attached importance to developing friendly
relations and cooperation with South Pacific countries, Jiang said,
adding this relationship has made significant progress owing to
joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
"At the dawn of the new century, we should value the importance
of our bilateral relations from a strategic height and try to find
and expand converging points of our common interests," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that both sides should redouble efforts to tap the
potential and expand bilateral exchanges and cooperation in the
economic, trade, scientific and technological, cultural and other
fields on the basis of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
"We should view and address our differences and disagreements
in the spirit of mutual respect and seeking common ground while
shelving differences so as to promote a steady and sound
development of bilateral ties," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed, "I am confident that as long as the two sides
make concerted efforts and take a broad and long-term view, our
friendly relations and cooperation will register new development
in the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
At the dinner, Shipley described Jiang's ongoing visit as "a
new and historic occasion in the relationship" between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
"As an independently-minded global trade, we look to build
strong relations with countries that matter to us," she said,
adding "China most certainly matters."
</P>
<P>
She said, "Through such groupings as APEC and, we hope soon,
the World Trade Organization, New Zealand and China are partners
in the pursuit of development, stability and growth."
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand-China relationship is established on firm
foundations - including New Zealand's commitment to a "One China"
policy, she said.
</P>
<P>
She specially mentioned one New Zealander, Rewi Alley, who made
an outstanding contribution to the relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Rewi Alley is well remembered in China, she said, adding how
happy he would have been, to see the first Chinese president visit
his hometown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
