<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's August Inflation Sinks to 36-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- British inflation rate fell to
1.1 percent in August, the lowest since July 1963, the Office for
National Statistics (ONS) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Underlying inflation, or RPIX, fell to 2.1 percent, the lowest
rate since October 1994, from 2.2 percent in July, said the ONS.
</P>
<P>
The fall comes less than a week after the Bank of England
raised British interest rates by 0.25 percentage point to 5.25
percent, even though RPIX was comfortably below the government's 2.
5 percent target.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said the main downward effects on inflation in August
were from seasonal food, particularly potatoes, and to a lesser
extent from non-seasonal food. There was also a small downward
effect from clothing and footwear.
</P>
<P>
It added that the largest offsetting upward effect came from
motoring costs. Petrol prices rose strongly as a result of higher
crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Most economists expected this rise in oil prices will put a
floor under inflation in coming months.
</P>
<P>
Goods inflation was particularly benign in August, sinking to 0.
5 percent, its lowest since records began in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
