<HEADLINE> HK Staff in Aircraft Rescue Operation Commended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Anson Chan, administrative
secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China
(HKSAR), Tuesday praised a group of front-line staff for their
efforts in the rescue operations during an air accident at Hong
Kong's airport on August 22.
</P>
<P>
"By your action and conduct, we have kept casualties to a
minimum and averted a catastrophe," Chan told a reception
organized by the government for more than 100 rescue workers from
over 15 government departments and airport, medical, and voluntary
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Chan said that if it had not been for the staff's exemplary act
of courage and gallantry, the consequence of the accident would
have been "unthinkable."
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred when a Taiwan MD-11 airliner flipped
upside down as it was landing in a tropical storm at Hong Kong
international airport on August 22. Three people were killed and
more than 200 injured in the accident.  
