<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open Posts Wider to Overseas Operators (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China will introduce even
more overseas funds, technology and expertise into its postal
services so as to improve the competitiveness of the industry.
</P>
<P>
Postmaster General Liu Liqing told a press conference at the
ongoing 22nd Universal Postal Congress here today that China is to
seal two agreements on joint ventures in the express mail service
(EMS) with the Netherlands later this month.
</P>
<P>
Posts of the Netherlands has been privatized and has become one
of the most profitable postal services in the world. It has bought
up TNT, a well-known international parcel delivery company.
</P>
<P>
Overseas operators now control 55 percent of China's EMS market.
They are still expanding the market shares in the country.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that in order to maintain and expand the market
position of the Chinese EMS, the State Postal Bureau (SPB) has
planned to join hands with large international operators to
improve competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
He said that China posts will also introduce overseas expertise
in new areas of postal services, including E-commerce.
</P>
<P>
During the 22nd Universal Postal Congress in Beijing, the SPB
signed an agreement with the Canadian post office on developing E-
commerce service. A similar agreement with Belgium is under
discussion now.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that China will focus on developing modernized postal
network and providing news services on the network in terms of
cooperation with foreign postal operators and administrations.
</P>
<P>
China has already signed agreements with Britain, the United
States, France and Russia on training and joint development of
international and domestic postal services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
