<HEADLINE> China to Open Posts Wider to Overseas Operators (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For example, China will send 15 senior postal managers to
Britain for training later this year. It has already sent three
groups of postal personnel to Britain this year.
</P>
<P>
China and France have reaffirmed recently that they will carry
out an agreement on cooperation of postal aviation. The French
post office will use its management expertise to help turn the
money-losing aviation fleet of its Chinese counterpart into
profits.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the development of postal infrastructure is
unbalanced among different areas of the country, he said that
China will continue to import overseas technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The SPB placed an order of 30 million U.S. dollars worth of
postal equipment with an German company recently.
</P>
<P>
He said that in order to turn China's postal services into a "
vigorous, efficient, competitive and profitable" business, the SPB
will continue to strengthen the profitable sectors of its
operations.
</P>
<P>
One of the sectors is savings deposit at post office. Liu said
here today that the State Council and the central bank have
already approved the establishment of a savings bank under the
post office.
</P>
<P>
An SPB official said that the savings bank will have a much
smaller scope of operation than Chinese commercial banks. It will
not have the right to issue loans. However, it may be allowed to
involve in insurance and other special operations.
</P>
<P>
Postal savings now account for over 47 percent of the total
revenue of the post office in China. By the end of 1998, the net
balance of savings deposits at the post office reached 306.5
billion yuan, accounting for six percent of the country's total
savings deposits.
</P>
<P>
China posts has an annual business volume of 16.62 billion yuan,
which is growing at 8-9 percent every year. It has 480,000
employees and 84,132 branches and offices around the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
