<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Banks Hike Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 14 (Xinhua) (C Two Zimbabwean major banks,
the First Banking Corporation and the Commercial Bank have
announced increases in their minimum yearly lending rates by three
percent to 53.75 percent and 52. 5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In separate statements on Tuesday, the banks said the increases
had been caused by changes in market conditions and an upward
trend in treasury bill rates.
</P>
<P>
The commercial bank also announced that its deposit rates would
be revised upwards.
</P>
<P>
Other leading financial institution, Standard Chartered and
Stanbic recently hiked their lending rates by three percent to
52.5 percent and 51 percent per annum respectively in response to
the impact of monetary policy on market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the increases were not surprising since all
major commercial banks would increase rates to cushion themselves
against inflation.
</P>
<P>
The country's year-on-year inflation by August had risen 5.3
percentage point to an unprecedented level of 68.8 percent from
July's 63.5 percent further compounding fears that the
International Monetary Fund's 30 percent target before the end of
the year would not be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Local economists believe that inflation was expected to reach
70 percent next month before it starts to come down to at least
40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
