<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Unhappy Over Dhaka's Slow Reform Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of Bangladesh's
donor countries and agencies at a two-day review meeting which
ended here Tuesday were critical of the country's political
situation, deteriorating law and order and the slowdown in overall
reform process.
</P>
<P>
They hinted at the possibility of reducing soft-term loans to
Bangladesh if the government failed to make substantive progress
in the pace of institutional reforms and in addressing the
country's structural problems.
</P>
<P>
The donors expressed concern at the government's eviction of
slum dwellers and sex workers earlier this year without ensuring
their rehabilitation, which they said might raise questions among
the donors about the human rights issue in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The flow of poverty alleviation fund might be affected if the
evicted slum dwellers and sex workers were not rehabilitated, they
observed.
</P>
<P>
World Bank country director Frederick T. Temple said although
the country's economic growth had been better than expected, the
government failed to make much headway with the structural reforms
necessary to unlock the private sector's economic potential.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed concern over the time-consuming and expensive
meeting like this and said the reform agenda should be as specific
as possible in addressing the concern. "Such meetings should only
be held if they are helpful in increasing our mutual understanding
of each others' concern and, perhaps, more importantly, in
furthering the reform agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
Resident representative of the International Monetary Fund
Ronald Hick suggested the government accelerate the reform in the
financial sector, saying that the problem in the financial sector
of the country was deep-rooted and structural reforms were
required to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
A document presented by the donors at the meeting recommended
good governance, sustainable political leadership, checking
corruption, ensuring human rights and accelerating reform programs
in the financial sector as the priority areas to achieve a stable
macro-economic growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the donors' concern, Finance Minister Shah A.M.S.
Kibria, who is also chairman of the Bangladesh Development Forum,
said the government had been continuing its effort to ensure basic
human rights of all citizens, accusing the opposition parties of
trying to foil the government's development activities by
enforcing strikes and creating anarchy.
</P>
<P>
A handout of the Press Information Department said the finance
minister expressed satisfaction at the review meeting and hoped
that views expressed by donor representatives would help expedite
development programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
Detailed discussions were held on governance and institutional
issues, financial sector reform and micro-credit, education,
health, nutrition, HIV/AIDS, arsenic, food security, and project
implementation, the handout said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of 23 donor countries and agencies attended the
mid-term review meeting, which took place nearly six months after
the "Bangladesh Development Forum Meeting" was held in Paris in
April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
