<HEADLINE> Chinese Customs Revenues Pass 100 Billion Yuan Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Customs revenues
amounted to 103.69 billion yuan (12.5 billion U.S. dollars) in the
first eight months of this year, an all-time high, according to
the General Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
Of that amount, 2.13 billion yuan went to tax refunds and 101.
56 billion yuan to state coffers, a 106 percent increase from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Officials here attribute the rise to the country's fight
against smuggling and closing of illegal import channels.
</P>
<P>
From January to July, Customs officers dealt with more than 7,
500 cases of smuggling and seized 3.747 billion yuan worth of
goods. The crackdown on smuggling will continue, the
administration says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
