<HEADLINE> Canada Suspends Arms Sales to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada has followed the
European Union and the United States in suspending military sales
to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Globe and Mail newspaper Tuesday quoted Canadian Foreign
Minister Lloyd Axworthy as announcing an indefinite ban on the
sales on his trip to Fiji Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ban involves export permits valued at more than 300 million
Canadian dollars (about 204 million U.S. dollars) in terms of fire-
control radar, military aircraft and components, and thermal-
imaging equipment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The ban came hours after the EU announced a suspension of four
months in all arms sales to Indonesia amid reports of violence in
East Timor since the end of August.
</P>
<P>
The United States took a similar move last Thursday, saying it
was breaking off military cooperation with Indonesia and
suspending military sales. 
</P>
