<HEADLINE> China Hopes for Five Golds in Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEINAN, SHAANXI, China, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China is
aiming for five weightlifting gold medals in the 2000 Olympic
Games, a top weightlifting official said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have set the goal of five golds in the Olympics as our
strongwomen enjoy clear upperhands in the world," said Qian
Guangjian, secretary general of the Chinese Weightlifting
Association.
</P>
<P>
China will dispatch eight strongmen and four strongwomen for
the Sydney Olympics as the women weightlifting will make its debut
in the biggest sport gala in the world with a total of 15 golds at
stake, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
However, the competition rules only grant China four berths in
the seven categories of the women's weightlifting in the coming
Olympics, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The three-day women's competitions in the fourth Chinese City
Games were concluded here on Tuesday with 21 strongwomen breaking
17 world records 44 times.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuejiu jerked up a new national record in the 58kg class in
the women's weightlifting whereas all but one Chinese records
surpass the world marks.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Diao Weiwei, Liu Haixia and Ding Meiyuan, equalized
three best marks in the world in the 63kg, 69kg and 75kg
categories.
</P>
<P>
The City Games also witnesses a promosing environment with a
string of young strongwomen as 12 of the top three finishers in
the seven categories are under the age of eighteeen, with 58kg
runner-up Wang Li only aged at 14.
</P>
<P>
However, concerned authorities are aware of the fact that only
one national record was broken despite 17 world marks were
surpassed.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Chinese strongwomen still lack competitive
capabilities in certain categories as 12 competitors failed to
surpass a single world mark in the 53kg, whereas the two-lift
national total in the 75-kg class is shy of the world mark by 2.5
kgs. 
</P>
