<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Expected To Attain Five Pct GDP Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is expected to
achieve a higher growth rate of 5 percent in the current fiscal if
weather conditions remain favorable and the agricultural sector
performs better, Asian Development Bank (ADB) said in a report
available here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth during 2000 is projected
as 5 percent. The agricultural sector is anticipated to maintain
the average growth rate of recent years provided weather condition
remains favorable," the Manila-based bank said in its Asian
Development Outlook Update.
</P>
<P>
The report said the country's 1998-99 GDP was revised to grow
at 4.8 percent after a bumper harvest of its winter paddy. A
previous estimate was around 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the country's food grain production might reach
21.4 million tons in 1998-99 as against 20.7 million tons in the
previous year, due to a recovery drive launched by the government.
</P>
<P>
It said that although the agricultural sector has apparently
overcome the impact of the floods, manufacturing sector growth is
estimated to have slipped to 2.8 percent from 9.2 percent of the
preceding year.
</P>
<P>
Despite a large inflow of external assistance, the foreign
exchange reserves declined to 1.5 billion U.S. dollars at the end
of 1999 from 1.7 billion U.S. dollars in the corresponding period
last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said the country's budget deficit also rose to 5.3 percent
of GDP compared with 4.2 percent of GDP in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The deficit has increased due to a flood-induced fall in
revenues and an increase in public expenditure, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report forecast the country's inflation at 8 percent in the
current fiscal year from an average of 9 percent in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The report said "the greatest challenge facing the government
is to revive economic and institutional reforms to reduce
pervasive poverty."
</P>
<P>
The bank said Bangladesh could only overcome the challenge
through prudent macroeconomics management and reforms in financial
and administrative sector, and private sector development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
