<HEADLINE> Nigeria Promotes Telecom in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A new rural telephone service
will soon be introduced by the Nigerian government, a Nigerian
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian quoted Nigerian Minister of State for
Communication Alhaji Elewi as saying in the country's western Oyo
State at the weekend that arrangements have been concluded for the
take-off of the new scheme called " wireless/cordless local loop"
.
</P>
<P>
He said the rural telephone service, when introduced, would be
made affordable to enable rural dwellers to enjoy telephone
services in line with the present government's policy not to make
the service the exclusive right of the rich.
</P>
<P>
Elewi reiterated government's determination to make telephone
services accessible to all Nigerians at affordable cost.
</P>
<P>
While explaining the scheme's mode of operation, the minister
said like its name "wireless," the rural telephone would be
operated without telecommunications wire, yet it would be
affordable and reliable.
</P>
<P>
In line with the new policy, the minister said three new
national telephone companies would be introduced to compete with
the Nigeria Telecommunications Limited (NITEL).
</P>
<P>
He said the monopoly being enjoyed by NITEL is affecting the
people who are being exploited.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed the belief that with the new three
national carriers and NITEL, people will get better services.
</P>
</TEXT>
