<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Concludes Visit to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Abdullah Bin
Hussein left here Tuesday for Amman, winding up his landmark visit
to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The visit by King Abdullah, who is the first Hashemite monarch
to visit Lebanon in almost three-and-a-half decades, came
following an invitation by Lebanese President Emile Lahoud during
his visit to Jordan in May.
</P>
<P>
The king arrived here on Monday accompanied by Prime Minister
Abdel Raouf al-Rarabdeh, Speaker of House of Representatives Abdul
Hadi Al Majali, Speaker of the Senate Zeid Rifai and Foreign
Minister Abdel-Ilah al-Khatib.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay, the king held talks with Lahoud,
Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime Minister Salim Hoss on
bilateral ties and regional affairs.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said the king's visit opened new horizon in
Lebanese-Jordanian relations.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Jordan and Lebanon cooled after Jordanian late
King Hussein signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994. Lebanon
and its main power broker Syria have territorial dispute with the
Jewish state, which is occupying Syrian Golan Heights and a border
strip in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has been following the foreign policy of Syria, which
is ostensibly stationing 350,000 troops in Lebanon to help
maintain its post-civil war stability.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Jordan and Lebanon has been improving, especially
after Syrian President Haffez Assad attended the Hussein's funeral
in February and Abdullah made a visit to Damascus in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
