<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UPU Head Sees Beijing Congress as Century's Most Important Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The 22nd Universal Postal
Congress (UPC) being held in Beijing is the most important event
of the world's postal sector in this century, Director of the
International Bureau of the Universal Postal Union (UPU) Thomas
Leavey said here today.
</P>
<P>
The congress, scheduled for conclusion on Wednesday, has
adopted the Beijing Postal Strategy for postal services all over
the world for the next five years following discussions on the
most pressing issues facing the postal sector, Leavey told a press
conference this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Postal Strategy calls on postal administrations and
operators around the world to utilize advanced electronic
technologies.
</P>
<P>
Leavey said that though electronic alternatives pose a great
challenge to traditional postal business, posts can turn the
information technology into its own advantage by exploiting such
new areas as e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
"Those who think we are a dying industry should read the
Beijing Postal Strategy," he said, noting that posts will always
be a key element of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Beijing congress has set many "first" in
the history of the UPU. It is the most attended meeting, with more
than 2,300 representatives from 183 countries and 33 international
organizations participating.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in the 125-year history of the UPU, the
Beijing congress decided to put the right to universal postal
services into the Acts of the UPU.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing congress attracted, also for the first time,
representatives from posts-related sectors such as private
operators, non-government organizations, manufacturers of postal
equipment and information technology industries to participate.
</P>
<P>
Liu Liqing, postmaster general of the State Postal Bureau, said
that the Beijing congress is a "milestone" in the history of UPU.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China will lead the reform and development of the
world postal sector in the next five years by assuming the
chairmanship of the UPU Council of Administration.
</P>
<P>
"We will take into consideration the interests of all countries
and try our best to do a good job," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
