<HEADLINE> Jiang Calls for Closer China-New Zealand Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here Tuesday that it is of great importance to
strengthen the relations between China and New Zealand in the new
international and regional situation.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon hosted in his honor by Governor-General of New
Zealand Michael Boys, Jiang Zemin said relations between China and
New Zealand have shown a good momentum of all-round development
with increasingly frequent exchanges of high-level visits, steady
growth of economic relations and trade and constantly broadened
scope of cooperation in recent years.
</P>
<P>
People-to-people contacts have become closer with the formal
launching of a tourist program that encourages Chinese citizens to
travel to New Zealand as tourists, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have stepped up dialogue and cooperation on major
international and regional issues, Jiang said, expressing China's
profound appreciation over the great contribution made by Governor-
General Michael Boys to the development of the relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin said he and Prime Minister of New Zealand Jenny
Shipley reached wide consensus on bilateral ties and international
issues of common interest.
</P>
<P>
"We both agreed that our two countries should look into the
future, view and approach bilateral relations in a strategic
perspective and work together to establish a 21st-century-oriented,
all-round cooperative relationship of long-term stability and
sound development," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also said New Zealand is dedicated to developing
exchanges and cooperation with Asia and has played a positive role
in maintaining peace in the world at large and the Asia-Pacific in
particular and promoting economic cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president also expressed appreciation and
congratulations to New Zealand on the successful convocation of
the 7th informal meeting of leaders of the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC).
</P>
<P>
Michael Boys said the visit by President Jiang Zemin to New
Zealand, the first ever paid by a Chinese head of state, is a
historic one which is of great significance to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Boys said the cooperative relationship between New Zealand and
China dates back to many years ago, and now with modern
transportation and technology, China is becoming an ever-closer
neighbor, and an immensely important one to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
He said the current visit by the Chinese president offered an
unparalleled opportunity of further developing the relationship
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Business and trading links are of the greatest
importance, but they must be complemented by personal contacts of
other kinds, such as through educational exchanges and tourism. It
is my profound hope that there will be strong growth in these most
valuable areas." 
</P>
</TEXT>
