<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Iraq's Kurdish Democratic Party (KDP) representative
in Turkey Sefin Dizayi has announced that the KDP had sent 2
million liters of diesel fuel to quake-hit Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Local Daily News Tuesday quoted Dizayi as saying that the
earthquake in Turkey caused great sorrow among its people, adding
that "all people should try to help one another in difficult
situations."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "we would have liked to provide more
help. However, due to the economic difficulties encountered in
Iraq, the best we could do was to send the Turkish government 2
million liters of diesel fuel."
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Elbit Systems can receive orders worth
over 140 million U.S. dollars in the coming five years to supply
equipment for F-16 fighter planes to U.S. aeronautical giant
Lockheed Martin Corp, the company said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Haifa-based Eibit Systems will supply Lockheed Martin with a
variety of equipment for planes including mission computers,
helmet mounted systems, display systems and stores management
systems.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- IDE Technologies, a subsidiary of Israel
Chemicals, has won together with Oceana Advanced Industries a
120-million-dollar contract for the establishment of desalination
plant in Cyprus, IDE said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two companies will build the plant and sell the water to
the government for a 10-year period. Once the contract ends, the
project will be transferred to the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's economy will finally turn around next
year, with growth rising to 3 percent and unemployment falling
from 8.9 percent to 8.7 percent, the Finance Ministry predicted in
a new economic forecast issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast gave four factors for the turnaround: an end to
the decline in immigration, the bottoming-out of the local
business cycle, an expected increase in tourism and an
improvement in the worldwide economy.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) and Algeria have
expressed satisfaction with the stability in petroleum markets
thanks to the production cut by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) member states and non-OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic Alam Al Yom newspaper said that Algerian Minister of
Energy and the current OPEC Chairman Youcef Yousfi has expressed
the belief that the March 1999 agreement to cut petroleum
production will remain in force until March 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
