<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Exports 58,900 Tons of Fish, Prawn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar exported a total of
58,900 tons of fish and prawn in fiscal 1998-99 which ended in
March, a 7.6 percent increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Figures provided by the country's Central Statistical
Organization indicate that of the total export volume, fish
accounted for 45,700 tons and prawn 13,200 tons.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings of fish and prawn in 1998-99 totaled 149.3
million U.S. dollars, 3.3 percent more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's annual per capita fish and prawn consumption is 18
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, whose coastline extends 2,276 kilometers, is rich in
fishery resources. The country's fish and prawn breeding ponds
cover 40,680 hectares with annual fish and prawn output from the
ponds amounting to 90,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Myanmar's rivers flow crisscross and fresh water
fish, caught in rivers, amount to 150,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The country's average annual production of fish and prawn tops
910,000 tons, of which over 240,000 tons are fresh water fish and
prawn, and 670,000 tons are deep sea fish and prawn.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar adopted an open-door economic policy in late
1988, foreign investment, injected into the fishery sector,
reached 197 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Teachers Urged to End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
asked the Academic Staff Union of Universities (ASUU) to suspend
its strike while its earnest negotiation with the body will be
resumed next Monday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the university teachers in Abuja on Monday,
Chief Philip Asiodu, chairman of the presidential panel on ASUU,
said President Olusegun Obasanjo would do "everything possible to
arrest the chaotic situation in our universities," the Guardian, a
leading Nigerian newspaper, reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Appealing to the aggrieved teachers to stop their strike which
began on Monday, Asiodu, who is also the chief economic adviser to
the president, assured them of the government's "sincerity in
reaching an acceptable agreement at next week's dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Tunde Adeniran Monday briefed the government
team on salaries and other conditions of services of the
university teachers.
</P>
<P>
Adeniran told The Guardian that the government would go ahead
with its planned negotiation with ASUU, expressing the confidence
that something tangible would be achieved.
</P>
<P>
On ASUU's position that the government should implement the
agreement the body reached with the former military regime,
Adeniran implored ASUU to understand that there is a difference
between a military and democratic government.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The difference between a military and a democratic
government is that the military can take decisions by fiat but a
democratic government will have to follow laid down rules."
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to addressing ASUU's problems. We are
currently doing that," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
