<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Howard: E.Timor Operation Could Result in Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard Tuesday warned that the East Timor peacekeeping
operation would be dangerous and could result in casualties.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a danger. There could be casualties and the
Australian public should understand that," he told ABC television.
"It is a serious, dangerous operation."
</P>
<P>
"All I can say is they (the peacekeeping force) will be given
adequate legal authority to defend themselves and to take whatever
action is necessary to implement their mandate," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the deployment timing still depends on the outcome of
the U.N. Security Council meeting in New York which could take
another day or two. Troops would be ready to move 24-48 hours
after that.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way that I will allow Australian forces to be
exposed to an unreasonable level of risk," he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the peacekeeping force would need to establish some
kind of working relationship with the Indonesian military as there
would be some initial contact between the U.N. forces and the
Indonesians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
