<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Fails to Hand Over Indian Soldiers Due to Disagreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Tuesday failed to
hand over two Indian soldiers captured last month as planned to
the International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) due to a
disagreement on the way of transfer.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Office spokesman Rafiq Altaf, addressing a
press briefing here, said Pakistan wanted to hand over the
captives under the glare of media to refrain India from any
anti-Pakistan propaganda.
</P>
<P>
"We want the journalists to witness that they are safe, sound,
in good health and good shape," he said.
</P>
<P>
India, however, insisted that the handover be done quietly and
without the presence of journalists, accusing Pakistan of
utilizing the soldiers for propaganda.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC could not receive the two Indian soldiers as
scheduled, because the international organization's such
activities should be done with the consent of both parties
concerned, Altaf said.
</P>
<P>
He rejected India's accusation, saying that Pakistan offered to
release the soldiers immediately after capturing them but India
refused to receive them because it wanted to deny its attack on
Pakistan's post.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan has to be careful because India had used
soldiers and dead bodies that Pakistan handed over to it to carry
out anti-Pakistan propaganda.
</P>
<P>
According to Pakistan, the two soldiers were captured in an
attack on Pakistani post in Shyok-Turtok sector across the Line of
Control by Indian troops late August.
</P>
<P>
India had denied such an attack and till only one day ago did
it agreed to the repatriation of its two soldiers through the
ICRC, said Altaf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
