<HEADLINE> U.N. East Timor Compound May Be Burning: AAP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations compound
in Dili was believed to be burning Tuesday night just hours after
the U.N. shut it down and airlifted 1,500 East Timorese refugees
to Australia, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
AAP quoted U.N. staff, who arrived in Darwin in northern
Australia from East Timor capital Dili, as saying they saw a black
plume of smoke rising from the direction of the abandoned
compound.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Assistance Mission to East Timor (UNAMET) Tuesday
pulled out most of its staff to Australia, leaving a token force
of 12 military liaison officers in the well-fortified Australian
consulate building in Dili.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the mission also evacuated more than 1,000 refugees
to Darwin following the approval of Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, UNAMET chief Ian Martin said in Darwin that conditions
in the  UNAMET Dili compound were no longer tenable. 
