<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Vice-President on Child Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti has said that the Kenyan government will soon introduce a
children's bill in Parliament with a view to enhancing the
protection of minors.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a five-day Third African Conference on Child Abuse
and Neglect which opened Monday in the Kenyan capital Nairobi,
the vice- president said his government will also address the
ratification of existing regional treaties on the elimination of
child labor.
</P>
<P>
He told the participants from Australia and the United States
as well as countries from Africa, Latin America and Europe that
millions of children live in difficult conditions and are denied
access to food, shelter, education, medical care and security.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti was quoted as saying by local press Tuesday that the
prevalence of war in Sub-Sahara Africa is a major factor that has
terminated lives among adults and children.
</P>
<P>
He said children in such circumstances are at the risk of
malnutrition, diseases and possibly death.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president urged all stakeholders in Sub-Sahara Africa
to channel their resources and energies to fight poverty.
</P>
<P>
He named poverty as a contributing factor to child labor,
saying the Kenyan government has reaffirmed its commitment to
poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that that more than 80 million children in
Africa are engaged in child labor.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the participants will discuss problems
on child protection, child labor and HIV/AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
