<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Party Daily Hails Success of APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese Communist
Party's daily Nhan Dan (The People) said Tuesday that the 7th
informal meeting of the leaders of the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum has affirmed the region's strong
commitment to urgent regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
Nhan Dan in a commentary described the informal meeting of APEC
leaders, which ended in New Zealand's Auckland on Monday, as a
successful one.
</P>
<P>
It said the Auckland declaration of the meeting affirmed APEC's
commitment to addressing urgent regional and international issues,
particularly those to be discussed in the coming round of talks by
the World Trade Organization (WTO), which is considered "a round
of talks spanning centuries."
</P>
<P>
The declaration entitled "The Auckland Challenge," adopted by
APEC leaders before the end of the meeting, also reflected the
desire of all APEC member economies to build an open, highly
competitive global eco-trade system based on mutual interests, the
daily noted.
</P>
<P>
"The Auckland forum has created favorable opportunities for
leaders of economies to establish new partnerships," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Bilateral meetings conducted on the sidelines of the summit
such as those between China and the United States, China and
Russia, Russia and the United States, and China and Japan, not
only covered bilateral relationships but also sought ways to boost
multilateral cooperation, thus contributing to obtaining APEC
goals, as well as to peace, stability, cooperation and development
in the Asia-Pacific region and in the world," it added.
</P>
<P>
However, the daily said that much remains to be done by APEC on
the path ahead which is full of both opportunities and challenges.
"APEC's achievements over the past decade and the fruitful results
of the Auckland Summit have helped strengthen a general confidence
in a strong and prosperous APEC in the future," it said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also said that the Vietnamese delegation headed
by Prime Minister Phan Van Khai made active contributions to the
success of the Auckland summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
