<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Proposes Asia-Latin America Trade Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada will explore the possibility of setting up a trade forum
between East Asia and Latin America during his coming visit to
Chile and Argentina, the Philippine government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Palace said in a news release that Estrada
made the remarks in Auckland, New Zealand, when he held bilateral
meetings with Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori and Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
They were all attending the annual Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) summit there.
</P>
<P>
The release said these talks, focusing on strengthening the
Philippines' economic ties with these countries, were part of the
country's effort to examine a possible free trade accord with
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
"Since we share common historical and cultural heritage with
these countries, the Philippines intends to serve as a bridge for
developing closer linkages between East Asia and Latin America,"
the president was quoted by the release as saying.
</P>
<P>
Estrada will proceed from Auckland on September 15 to Chile and
Argentina for state visits. It will be the first time that a
Philippine president will visit these two countries.
</P>
<P>
With these visits, the president will take the lead among East
Asian nations in discussing the prospects for a trade forum with
Latin America to reinforce trade links between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Manila serves as the "natural gateway" to Asia for goods and
services from Latin America, but has yet to fully take advantage
of this as shown by the small percentage of trade with this region
as compared with the Philippines' neighbors in the Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the Philippines and Argentina and Chile were
valued at 40 million U.S. dollars and 51 million dollars
respectively in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
