<HEADLINE> Both Share Prices, Dollar Fall in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices turned downward in
Tokyo Tuesday, dragged down by the yen's rise against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 132.07 points, or 0.74
percent, from Monday's close to end at 17,777.22.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 10.44 points or 0.68 percent to 1,
524.79.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 565.94 million
shares from 597.48 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Electronic Corp. was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
After opening higher, the Nikkei index stayed in minus
territory throughout the day, and fell to as low as 17,610.31 just
after the afternoon session started.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were lower in most business sectors, and traders
noted export-oriented technology issues were weak, hit by the yen'
s strength and the unfavorable performance in the Nasdaq index
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far exceeded
gainers 786 to 421, with 137 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar fell briefly to
106.00 yen, its lowest level in Tokyo since May 15, 1996,
prompting the Bank of Japan to conduct dollar-buying intervention
in the market.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the U.S. currency was quoted at 106.55-58 yen, down
from 106.62-65 yen at 9 a.m., and from 106.65-75 yen in New York
overnight. The dollar traded at 107.77-80 yen in Tokyo late Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yen-buying was strong in Tokyo as hopes for Japan's economic
pickup were fueled by the release last Thursday for better-than-
expected Japanese gross domestic product (GDP) figures, a dealer
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
