<HEADLINE> Tokyo Athletics Meet Draws Big Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The world's fastest man Maurice
Greene of the United States will spearhead a strong field of world
champions and record holders at the Tokyo track and field meet
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Greene, 25, who set a world 100 meters record of 9.79 seconds
in June, will launch the final shot of the season as a heavy
favorite in the men's 100m race.
</P>
<P>
The American, however, will face a strong challenge from Jason
Gardener of Britain, seventh in Seville world championships this
August. Local hero Koji Ito, holder of the Asian record in 100m,
American Kurtis Johnson and Yin Hanzhao of China will also pose
problems for Greene.
</P>
<P>
Colin Jackson of Britain was another big star at the
international meeting, which features as many as 18 events and
some 150 athletes.
</P>
<P>
Jackson set the world 110m hurdles record of 12.91 seconds to
win the 1993 world championships and regained the title in Seville
with winning performance of 12.04.
</P>
<P>
Jackson's rivals in Tokyo will be 1999 U.S. champion Mark Crea
and his compatriot Larry Wade. Asian Games champion Chen Yanhao
of China will also pose a challenge to him.
</P>
<P>
1997 world indoor champion Kevin Little of the United States
will compete against Obadele Thompson of Barbados in the men's
200m.
</P>
<P>
American Antonio Pettigrew will race against world
championships bronze medalist Alejandro Cardenas of Mexico and
Asian Games champion Sugath Tilikaratne of Sri Lanka in the men's
400m.
</P>
<P>
Another attention-calling entry was the Susanthika Jayasinghe
of Sri Lanka, who has been struggling to regain her form in which
she emerged as the silver-medalist in 200m event at the 1997 world
championships.
</P>
<P>
Her career has been in limbo as she was caught up with the
doping charges but the world athletics ruling body IAAF is
expected to clear her.
</P>
<P>
The big absentees are pole vault world record holder Emma
George of Australia and three-time long jump world champion Ivan
Pedroso of Cuba who have pulled out with injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
