<HEADLINE> WWF Study Shows Toxic Contamination in Yugoslavia Spreading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- NATO's recent 78-day bombing
against Yugoslavia has led to toxic contamination in Yugoslavia,
the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
On publishing its expert team's analytical results confirming
evidence of damage to the environment through chemical
contamination, the WWF called for urgent clean-up of toxic
substances that continue to pollute the environment in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In a recent study, the WWF expert team assessed two of the
facilities bombed in Yugoslavia: The Pancevo petrochemical complex
and the Novi Sad oil refinery, and tested the water of the Danube
River. They found that toxic pollutants, originally released in
the immediate environment of bombed facilities, are now
threatening further damage by spreading into surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the WWF, samples taken from soil and water showed
the presence of notable quantities of mercury, polycyclic aromatic
hydrocarbons, ethylene dichloride, and other highly toxic
substances including dioxin.
</P>
<P>
"These were initially released by the bombing of industrial
complexes and continue to leach from these facilities, threatening
groundwater drinking supplies and natural resources in several
countries of the area," WWF said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
It urged the international donor community to provide financial
and technical support and equipment for the urgent clean-up and
removal of contaminants in both the soil and the water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
