<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Command Snubs Clash Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Military High Command of
Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) have rejected the report
about the August 14- 17 clashes between Ugandan and Rwandan troops
in Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The report, compiled by a joint committee and released last
week, blames Uganda more for the clashes which claimed hundreds
of lives, the Monitor daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In what amounted to a rejection of the report, the High
Command recommended that a panel be set up to make a broader and
fairer review of the bloody clashes.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan Vice President
Paul Kagame met in western Uganda on August 16-17 in a bid to stop
the clash from escalating.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, which both sent troops to back rival
factions of the main rebel group in the DRC conflict, accused
each other of inciting the fighting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
