<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day Special Profile: Female Lawyer Benefits from China's Improving Legal System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year is the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China. Xinhua News Agency is
releasing about 50 stories on Chinese men and women, young and old,
to illustrate the changes that have taken place in China over the
past half century. These people will describe their lives and how
they fit into the changes in the motherland. This is the 25th
story in the series.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua)-- Attorney Zhou Liying says she
is among the first batch of Chinese who have grown rich since
China opened to the outside world in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
During her ten-year legal career, she has not only witnessed
the speedy development of China's legal system, but also fattened
her own purse.
</P>
<P>
The petite 35-year-old talked to Xinhua about her job during an
interview at the Capital Club, one of Beijing's few playgrounds
for the rich and famous in an area dotted with embassies and
foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Zhou has had a steady caseload for quite some time and can be
choosy about which cases to take. Just ten years ago she was an
ordinary teacher.
</P>
<P>
In 1986, her bosses ordered her to switch from teaching finance
to economic law, saying that as the youngest teacher in Ningbo TV
University, she "should also be the most receptive to new
knowledge."
</P>
<P>
She studied in the evening and gave lectures the next morning
to students, mostly older than she.
</P>
<P>
After four years of teaching law, it occurred to her to make it
her career.
</P>
<P>
At the time she was analyzing the pros and cons of being an
attorney, then leader Deng Xiaoping announced that China needed
500,000 lawyers, and in 1979 swung open the doors to the legal
system, which had suspended for 22 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day Special Profile: Woman Lawyer Benefits from China's Improving Legal System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deng's words helped her to make the decision in an era when
changing jobs was still regarded as irresponsible. She passed the
bar exam and entered a government law office in early 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, her first job was far from rosy. "No matter how hard
you worked, the pay was set -- just 100 or 200 yuan a month," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Not only was the money bad, there was a general negative
perception of lawyers. "It was not news if a lawyer was thrown out
of court back then," she said, explaining that there were no laws
to protect the rights of lawyers, and what lawyers could
accomplish largely depended on how much information the police,
procurators and courts would give them.
</P>
<P>
"For ordinary people, lawyers are the sort of oily-tongued
people that help cover up for robbers and rapists and the like.
And there was a guy who even blurted out to me, 'A woman is a
lawyer?'"
</P>
<P>
In 1992, however, the legal profession improved markedly
because reforms enabled lawyers to charge clients individually for
cases.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Zhou resigned from her state job and opened her own
law firm specializing in financial matters. Business was so brisk
that by mid-1995 she had earned nearly one million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Foreseeing tough competition in the road ahead, Zhou left her
home Ningbo, a port city in east China's Zhejiang Province, to
come to Beijing where she studied international law in the
graduate program at the China University of Political Science and
Law. In 1997, in her final year of school, she joined the
prestigious Beijing W&AMP;H Law Firm, and developed a reputation as a
tough attorney capable of handling difficult cases.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that her clients are mainly companies, factories and
government institutions. But in the past few years, more and more
private citizens have sought legal help.
</P>
<P>
"They want their wills witnessed, and sometimes a man and woman
will witness to each other's assets before tying the knot," she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day Special Profile: Woman Lawyer Benefits from China's Improving Legal System (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The tiny minority of wealthy people want to have their own
lawyers," she concluded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she has had an increasing number of requests for
mediation services, which now make up more than half of her
workload, she said. She prefers mediating because court battles
are usually "unbearably lengthy." As a mediator, she acts as a
neutral party between two sides who try to work out their
differences without going to court, usually resolving the problem
within one or two months.
</P>
<P>
"Ten years ago, China had a very weak law system," she said. "
When troubles arose, people instantly thought of going to leaders
or finding connections for assistance. Now it's different. The
concept that law overrides power has been accepted as common sense
by more and more people."
</P>
<P>
She shook her head, recalling how difficult it was ten years
ago to convince anyone that the law is more influential than power.
</P>
<P>
She has handled 367 lawsuits so far and believes that "the
courts have judged cases on the basis of facts and on legal
principle." Still, there are a couple of cases she would love to
re-try.
</P>
<P>
Zhou admits that China's legal system is not yet sound and
complete, and there are still holes to close. But in the meantime,
she said, attorneys can study new laws and keep up with
developments in the legal profession.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promotes Water-Efficient Irrigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China will increase the acreage
of irrigated areas by three million hectares in the next 12 years,
according to an official from the Ministry of Water Resources (MWR)
.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of irrigated areas in China will rise from 40 percent
to 55 percent by the year 2010. Farmland equipped with water-
saving irrigation devices is expected to expand by 15 million ha.,
said Chen Lei, director of the Rural Water Resources Department of
the MWR in an interview with Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
The central authorities will allocate 1.25 billion yuan (151
million U.S dollars) in bonds to build 150 large cost-effective
irrigation projects and 130 smaller ones this year. Government
departments have arranged 3.2 billion yuan to help local
governments with irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in south China has pledged to
raise 100 million yuan this year to develop water-efficient
irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
The government of east China's Shandong Province has decided to
earmark 70 million yuan each year to spread the use of water-
saving facilities.
</P>
<P>
China's irrigated farmlands have sprawled from 16 million ha.
in 1949 to present 53 million ha. The country invested 25 billion
yuan in irrigation projects in the past three years. More
Investment will be used to this purpose in the future, Chen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
