<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Ready to Help Indonesia on East Timor Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan said Tuesday that his country will send troops to join
the United Nations peacekeeping force in East Timor after the U.N.
Security Council and Indonesia have come to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing and ready to help our closest friend,
Indonesia, on the East Timor issue," Surin said after meeting with
President B.J. Habibie at the Merdeka Palace here.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of Thailand leading the U.N. peacekeeping
force, Surin said the issue was not discussed during his meeting
with Habibie.
</P>
<P>
He said the Thai government is offering its humanitarian
assistance in its own capacity as it is not representing any
regional organization, including the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Other ASEAN countries will separately convey their readiness to
help Indonesia, said Surin, who arrived here Tuesday after
attending the just-concluded informal leaders meeting of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum in Auckland, New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Surin acted as chairman of the ASEAN Standing Committee during
the APEC meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I came here to convey the messages of Thailand's prime
minister who led Thailand at the APEC meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie announced Sunday his readiness to accept a peacekeeping
force through the United Nations to restore peace and security in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian military spokesman Maj. Gen. Sudrajat Monday said
Indonesia preferred to have more troops from ASEAN countries,
saying that they have the capabilities to understand more
objectively the complexity of the East Timor problem.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move has never been recognized by the
United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
