<HEADLINE> China's Exports to Major Partners Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China's exports to the United
States, Japan, and some other major partners in the first eight
months of the year grew remarkably from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the General Administration of Customs
Monday show that the total exports reached 118.4 billion US
dollars, down only 0.2 percent. The exports continued to grow for
a second consecutive month in August.
</P>
<P>
The United States remains the largest importer of China's
commodities. China's exports to the U.S. reached 25.92 billion US
dollars in the January-August period, up 12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The mainland's exports to Hong Kong declined 17.4 percent to 22.
39 billion US dollars. But the export volume grew 21.8 percent in
August, the first positive growth month since January.
</P>
<P>
The exports to Japan climbed 4.5 percent to 19.33 billion US
dollars and to the European Union soared 3.4 percent to 18.58
billion US dollars during the January-August period.
</P>
<P>
The exports to the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (
ASEAN) reached 7.44 billion US dollars, up 7.6 percent, and that
to the Republic of Korea topped 4.66 billion US dollars, up 19.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The exports to Taiwan edged up 0.4 percent to 2.44 billion US
dollars, and that to Australia surged 12.6 percent to 1.63 billion
US dollars, and that to Canada reached 1.50 billion US dollars, up
11.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The exports to Russia plummeted 44.1 percent in the first eight
months to 730 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
