<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Presidential Office to Be Entirely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki has formally moved his office from Cape Town to
Pretoria, although he will still have to fly to Cape Town when
parliament is in session, reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Previously the president alternated between two offices in Cape
Town and Pretoria, the legislative and administrative capitals of
the country.
</P>
<P>
But the government denied speculation that the move was a
prelude to a decision by the ruling African National Congress to
move parliament from Cape Town to Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said Monday that the
move was the result of organizational and administrative
considerations. It was also expected to save money.
</P>
<P>
"There is no relationship whatsoever between the decision taken
on the presidency and the debate about the seat of parliament.
These are two wholly separate matters," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
While the president could determine the base of the presidency,
he said, only parliament was empowered by the constitution to
determine the seat of the national legislature.
</P>
<P>
The decision to base the presidency entirely in Pretoria was
taken because the president was not a member of parliament,
although he was entitled to speak in parliament, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president was also not obliged to be present in parliament
except when making an address of national importance or during the
debate on his budget, said Mankahlana.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has already named Deputy President Jacob Zuma as leader
of government business in parliament, which means that Zuma will
be present in parliament and maintain the close relationship
between the presidency and the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki will have to fly to Cape Town to attend cabinet meetings
when parliament is in session because all ministers are parliament
members and must attend parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
