<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Appeals for Aid to 30,000 People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan opposition
United Front Tuesday launched an emergency appeal for
international aid to some 30,000 people beleaguered in the Darre
Suf valley in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"Without international assistance we feel that many will perish
in the coming months," General Sayed Hussain Anwari, an opposition
commander, said in a statement released from the valley in
Samangan province.
</P>
<P>
Since a major Taliban offensive on Darre Suf in February this
year, the valley has continually come under enemy fire, which has
resulted in the killing of many innocent people, Anwari said.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Taliban of indiscriminate attacks on
infrastructure in the valley which "have caused severe damage" to
the economy there.
</P>
<P>
Darre Suf is a strategically located valley with access to
northern and central Afghan provinces of Balkh, Bamiyan and
Sar-e-Pol.
</P>
<P>
The valley boasts one of Afghanistan's biggest coal mines.
Other sources of income in the valley include agricultural
products, fruits and livestock.
</P>
<P>
Anwari said the valley's population, mainly ethnic Tajiks,
Hazaras and Uzbeks, recently swelled to well over 30,000 people
following the Taliban's "atrocities" in Bamiyan and Balkh.
</P>
<P>
The opposition commander said 1,000 shops have been burnt, 100
hectares of land destroyed, 5,000 farm animals killed and 1
million fruit trees perished in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the above, we call on the international community
and humanitarian organizations to render urgently needed
assistance to the beleaguered population in the valley," he said.
</P>
<P>
Items of need include food products, clothing and medical aid,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
