<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Reveals How Companies Create Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Companies that achieve
attractive levels of profitability and then aggressively invest in
growth are more likely to increase shareholder value than those
focusing on restructuring alone, said a study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The growth focus has been more prevalent in the United States,
where company profitability has been higher, and the restructuring
focus more prevalent in Europe, said the study.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the U.S. management consulting firm,
the Boston Consulting Group, examined "total shareholder returns"
of some 5,300 public companies, which together account for 80
percent of the total capitalization of the world's stock markets,
from the end of 1993 through the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Total shareholder return (TSR) is defined as the capital gains
plus the dividend payments relative to the share price at the
start of the period, assuming immediate reinvestment of dividends.
The median TSR for all companies in the study was 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The top ten performers in terms of TSR included six American
companies and four European companies. Dell Computers ranked
number one, with an average annual TSR of 153 percent for each of
the five years, followed by American Online, 143 percent, and the
German software company SAP, 91 percent.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that six of the top ten companies come from
the information/communications and telecommunications sector,
which was the highest performing sector overall, followed by the
pharmaceutical and healthcare sector. Banking, retail and
insurance were also among the high-performing industries.
</P>
<P>
While overall market and economic conditions affect each
company's performance, the study found some primary means of
creating shareholder value are largely within the manager's
control. These include improvement in the company's cash-flow
margin, improvement in the productivity of the company's assets
and growth in investment.
</P>
<P>
The consulting firm said that growth has been the primary force
for increasing shareholder value in the United States. European
companies, by contrast, have largely relied on restructuring,
which results from asset productivity and cash-flow margin
improvements. Overall, profitable growth companies have created
more value than restructuring companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Blast Toll Rises to 112 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Monday's
apartment building blast in Moscow has reached 112, 11 of them
children, the Interfax news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 13 human body fragments were found, Interfax said,
quoting the press service of the Ministry for Emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Clean-up operation was continuing at the site where an eight-
story apartment building was demolished by a powerful explosion
early Monday, the third in Moscow since August 31, when a bomb
went off in an underground mall near the Kremlin. Last Wednesday,
a nine-story apartment building was also ripped apart by a blast.
</P>
<P>
One person died in the August 31 bombing and 94 people were
killed in the Wednesday blast.
</P>
<P>
In the Dagestani city of Buinaksk, an apartment blast killed 64
about a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Although none of the explosions has been solved, authorities
suspect that Chechen terrorists were involved.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo on Tuesday morning reported
on the latest findings of the investigation into the explosions to
President Boris Yeltsin, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Rushailo said law enforcement bodies are concentrating their
efforts on Moscow and other big cities. Security is being
tightened in public transport as well as at strategic facilities
controlled by the Atomic Energy Ministry and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after the meeting with Yeltsin that 3,800
kilograms of explosives were seized in raids following the Monday
bombing in Kashirskoye Shosse in southeast Moscow, the Itar-Tass
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In an apartment block in Borisovskye Prudy Street, which is not
far from Kashirskoye Shosse, police found 16 plastic charges
complete with a 70-meter fuse, Rushailo said.
</P>
<P>
The apartment building has been evacuated and the explosives
defused, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
