<HEADLINE> Inflation Rises to 68.8 Percent in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year
inflation has risen to an unprecedented level of 68.8 percent for
August amid growing fears that the International Monetary Fund's
30 percent target before the end of the year will not be achieved.
</P>
<P>
The rate has increased by 5.3 percentage points from July's
figure, meaning that prices as measured by the all items consumer
price index increased by an average of 68.8 percent in August
compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistical Office said on Monday the rise in
inflation was mainly caused by the increases in the price of
bread, cereals, meat, drink, fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said wage pressure, fuel price increases and
electricity tariffs would make it impossible for the rate to come
down dramatically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
