<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Consider Indonesian Objections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Minister of Home
Affairs Syarwan Hamid said Tuesday that the United Nations should
consider objections of the Indonesian people with regard to the
formation of a U.N. peacekeeping force to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"The objections of the people of Indonesia should be considered
by the U.N. not to involving Australia in the U.N. peacekeeping
force to East Timor," Hamid told reporters at the parliament here.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated that Indonesia is to leave the
formation of the U.N. peacekeeping force up to the U.N.
</P>
<P>
"But I think the U.N. will not take a risk with ignoring such
objections launched by the people of Indonesia (to exclude
Australia in the peacekeeping force)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a member of House Commission I for law, security and
foreign affairs, Yasril A. Baharuddin, insisted on Tuesday that
Australia should respect Indonesian sovereignty over East Timor
since the territory was still a part of Indonesia until the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) confirms the ballot result
which East Timorese voted to break with Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"But until then (MPR session in November) we still have
sovereignty over East Timor. We ask for Australia to honor it.
Don't interfere in our own internal problem in East Timor," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan met Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas on Monday, discussing the details of
the U.N. proposal of sending a peacekeeping force to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said his talks with Annan will continue Tuesday on a
number of issues including the composition and the nature of the
force and the role of the Indonesian army in the peacekeeping
mission.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie announced here Sunday night
that his government accepted the presence of a U.N. peacekeeping
force in cooperation with the country's military to restore order
and security in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Violence has taken place since the announcement of the August
30 ballot result in East Timor by the U.N. on September 4. The
result showed over 78 percent of the total East Timorese voters
favored independence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move has never been recognized by the
U.N. 
</P>
