<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day Special (National Day Special) China's Family Planning Policy Slows Down World Population Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Population
Fund predicts that the world population will hit six billion on
October 12 -- a historic instant that would have come three or
four years earlier had China failed to bring its population growth
under control, Chinese demographers say.
</P>
<P>
They also insist that the population control policy, or family
planning, will have to be carried out for a long time in China if
the world's most populated country wants to achieve sustainable
development in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
"Without taking effective measures to slow down the rapid
growth of population, China would have 300 million people more
than current figure of 1.248 billion, and 'World Day of Six
Billion People' would come much earlier," says Zhang Weiqing,
minister in charge of State Family Planning Commission (SFPC).
</P>
<P>
Professor Lin Fude, a researcher with the Demographic Institute
of People's University in Beijing, believes that the country would
have been more excessively burdened if those people had been born.
</P>
<P>
"The problems we face will not be simply in regard to the
supply of more food and clothing. Due to excessive consumption,
China may be overburdened by resource shortages and environmental
pollution, even the current situation has turned serious," he says.
</P>
<P>
Research shows that although annual grain output in 1996 was 90
billion kilograms more than the 1984 figure, the per capita intake
of grain in 1996 was eight kg less than 1984, which means the
growth of grain production was unable to meet the population
growth in that period.
</P>
<P>
A massive population also puts extra pressure on education,
medical care, welfare, traffic, housing, employment and other
social sectors, Prof. Lin says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-National Day Special (National Day Special) China's Family Planning Policy Slows Down World Population Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In contrast with the never-ending increase in the population
figure since New China was founded in 1949, the population-control
policy suffered a long-term setback until leaders implemented the
family planning strategy in the 1970s, when the population climbed
to some 900 million.
</P>
<P>
Considering the urgency of population control, the Communist
Party of China (CPC), the ruling party of the country, in 1982
announced that the family planning policy was a fundamental
national policy. The country's revised Constitution, which was
adopted in the same year, also stipulated that Chinese couples
would be obligated to follow the policy.
</P>
<P>
The family planning programs that also offer reproductive
health service are now available across the country, and have
adopted the policy that couples should marry and have a child
later in life and take steps to ensure a healthy birth.
</P>
<P>
China now keeps its birth rate at about 16 per thousand and the
population growth rate at 9.5 per thousand, both less than half of
the 1970's figures. China's population growth rate has been
approaching the level of some industrialized countries such as the
United States and Canada, according to the SFPC.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhang Weiqing stresses that population control will
continue to be a challenge for China because an average of 13
million people will be increased each year until the total
population stops growing in the middle of the next century.
</P>
<P>
According to an SFPC plan, China will control its population
within 1.4 billion by 2010 and will continue to lower incidence of
birth defects while improving reproductive health services and
overall quality of the people. Demographers predict that China's
population will reach the peak -- between 1.44 billion and 1.52
billion -- by the year 2031.
</P>
<P>
"In order to achieve the goal of grain sufficiency and
sustainable development at that time, China should make sure that
the population-control policy remains unchanged," Prof. Lin says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0281 </DOCNO>
