<HEADLINE> Australian Lamb Industry to Suffer Only in Short Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia's lamb industry is
expected to suffer from damaging U.S. tariffs in the short term
but to recover by 2001-2002, the country's chief commodities
forecaster said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Agriculture and Resource Economics
(ABARE) said the U.S. tariff rate quota would make it difficult
for the industry to continue increasing lamb exports to the United
States, but the long-term prospects were good.
</P>
<P>
In July, the United States outraged Australia when it imposed
the quota after its sheep farmers complained of huge volumes of
imports damaging the industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the new restrictions, a border tax of 9 percent will be
imposed on the first 31.85 million metric tons of imported lamb
and a 40-percent tariff will be added to lamb shipments above that
level.
</P>
<P>
"The imposition of the tariff rate quota is expected to
constrain the Australian industry's ability to continue to
increase lamb exports to the U.S. market," ABARE said in its
September quarter forecast.
</P>
<P>
But competitive lamb prices and the continued commitment by the
Australian industry would mean Australian exports should grow
again beyond 2001-2002, although not at the same high rate as
experienced in recent years, it said.
</P>
<P>
ABARE also expects lamb farmers to direct more exports to other
international markets, such as the United Kingdom, where
Australian exports increased by around 17 percent in 1998-99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
