<HEADLINE> U.N. Closes Besieged Dili Compound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Tuesday
closed its besieged compound in the East Timor capital of Dili
after the evacuation of 1,300 East Timorese to Australia, a U.N.
official said.
</P>
<P>
But the world body would leave about a dozen staff at a
different location in the city, Ian Martin, head of U.N.
Assistance Mission to East Timor (UNAMET), said in Darwin,
northern Australia.
</P>
<P>
Martin arrived in Darwin on the first of at least 12 flights
out of Dili bringing out the refugees and 110 non-essential UNAMET
staff.
</P>
<P>
"With their (the refugees) arrivals here we have closed the
UNAMET compound in Dili," Martin told reporters at Darwin
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
He said 12 UNAMET personnel would remain in Dili at another
location and would continue to assess the security situation and
liaise with the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
Martin said permission for the evacuation of the refugees, who
had been living in the UNAMET compound for about a week, had been
given personally by Indonesia President B.J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
"First I should say it was President Habibie himself who
authorized the departure of internationally displaced people,"
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
"That authorization had allowed a smooth evacuation in convoys
from the compound to the airport," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations had been working for some days to get the
necessary permission to evacuate the Timorese.
</P>
<P>
Martin said he was very concerned about UNAMET security in
Dili.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions in our compound are not really tenable," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations' 80 staff have been unable to leave the
compound for the past 10 days and were not able to work
effectively.
</P>
<P>
He said it made sense to relocate them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
