<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Kills 14 Million People in World: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 10.7 million of those killed were adults, of which 4.7
million were women.
</P>
<P>
These figures were disclosed by a summary compiled by the Joint
United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) as of December 1998
and circulated at the on-going 11th International Conference on
AIDS and STDS (sexually transmitted diseases) in Africa (ICASA) in
Lusaka. The summary says: " More than 95 percent of all
HIV-infected people now live in the developing countries, which
has likewise experienced 95 percent of all deaths to date from
AIDS, largely among young adults." According to the UNAIDS
and the World Health Organization (WHO), the epidemic killed at
least 3.2 million children below the age of 15 since it was
discovered.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 alone two million adults including 900,000 women died
from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Additionally 510,000 children below the age of 15 died after
acquiring HIV which leads to the disease.
</P>
<P>
The report says among 33.4 million people living with the
killer virus or AIDS are 13.8 million women and 1.2 million
children below 15 when the research was concluded last year.
</P>
<P>
"The epidemic has not been overcome anywhere. Virtually every
country in the world has seen new infections since 1998 and the
epidemic is frankly out of control in many places," the report
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0291 </DOCNO>
