<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Labor Ministry Acts to Help Labors in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Labor and Social Welfare
Ministry of Thailand is seeking to help thousands of Thai workers
in Israel facing low payment and poor living standard, the Bangkok
Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Domdej Bunnag, the Thai ambassador to Tel Aviv, told Labor
Minister Wut Sukosol, that most of the workers are paid 650-680
baht (17.1-17.9 U.S. dollars) daily despite Israel's minimum wage
of 780 baht (20.5 dollars) per day, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the minister as saying that the Employment
Department of the ministry was planning to require job brokers
responsible to pay the affected workers equal to the amounts their
Israeli employers owed them.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Labor Ministry had responded positively to the
ambassador's call for assistance, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
About 24,000 Thais work in Israel now, mostly in agricultural,
construction and service sectors. Israel has 8,000 job vacancies
for Thai workers.
</P>
<P>
Wut urged those looking for jobs in Israel to contact
provincial employment offices to avoid cheating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
