<HEADLINE> BOT May Delay Announcing Winner in Radanasin Bank Bidding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Central bank governor Chatu Mongol Sonakul was quoted as saying
that the delay was needed because the government's legal experts
are looking into the terms of the purchase agreement.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's United Overseas Bank was widely expected to win
Thai government approval last week for its bid to take over the
64-branch bank.
</P>
<P>
Radanasin, formerly Laem Thong Bank Plc, was nationalized in
August 1998 along with a few other banks after several months of
unsuccessful attempts to recruit a foreign strategic partner.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday Britain's Standard Chartered Bank announced that it
has acquired 75 percent of the equity and full management control
of Nakornthon Bank, another nationalized bank, for 12.377 billion
baht (334.5 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thai central bank official said buyers of Radanasin, Nakornthon
and two other state-controlled banks would need to hold their 75
percent stakes for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
They said the remaining 25 percent would be retained by a
central bank unit, the Financial Institutions Development Fund,
which planned to eventually list about 10 percent of the bank
stakes in the Thai stock market. 
