<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Offers to Talk With Opposition on Transshipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina Monday reiterated her call to the opposition to
discus the transshipment issue across the table or in the
parliament and shun their unnecessary destructive politics in the
form of hartal (general strike).
</P>
<P>
She noted that her government did not sign any pact with India
on transshipment or transit. "We have only decided, in principle,
for a discussion on transshipment to carry Indian goods in our
transports," she said, adding that the present government favors
discussion to do anything good for the betterment of the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation over Radio and Television on Monday night
on the eve of her departure for New York to attend the U.N.
General Assembly session, the prime minister referred to the
opposition's demand for canceling the transshipment agreement with
India and sought to know how they were placing such a demand as
there was no such agreement on the issue as yet.
</P>
<P>
The first day of the 60-hour countrywide hartal called by the
four opposition parties led by Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)
disrupted normal life and halted business and commercial
activities on Monday in the capital and elsewhere in the country.
The hartal left one dead and one hundred injured.
</P>
<P>
The hartal was called by the opposition to protesting what they
termed the police excesses on the opposition activists during
Sunday's "peaceful" sit-in demonstration in front of the
Bangladesh Secretariat and repression on the opposition activists.
</P>
<P>
The opposition staged the sit-in demonstration to protest the
government decision to provide corridor facility to India in the
name of transshipment.
</P>
<P>
The BNP-led opposition alliance on Monday threatened to
intensify their movement if the government continued its
repression of the opposition. Briefing newsmen in the evening,
BNP Secretary General Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan said that despite
repressive measures the government would not succeed in containing
the growing movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
