<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Will not Send Forces to East Timor: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister
Hun Sen said Tuesday that his country will not send forces to join
the U.N. peacekeeping forces because of problems in his own
country.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister of Cambodia fully welcomes the decision of
the Government of Indonesia to accept the multi-national
peacekeeping forces of the United Nations so as to restore and
strengthen order and stability in East Timor," a statement of the
spokesman of the prime minister sent from Cuba said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen just finished his four-day official visit to Cuba and
will leave there to take part in the U.N. General Assembly in New
York.
</P>
<P>
"The Kingdom of Cambodia is truly desired to participate in
seeking for security for the East Timorese people," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
"However," the prime minister explained, "due to the economic
and social problems Cambodia is facing now and the multisector
reforms, especially that of the armed forces, which now Cambodia
is undertaking, she is of no ability to send her forces to join
the operation in East Timor."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hun Sen said that "Cambodia cherishes strong hope
that the multi-national peacekeeping forces of the United Nations
will effectively cooperate with the Indonesian Government to
quickly and successfully set up peaceful situation for the people
of East Timor."
</P>
<P>
Prince Ranariddh, president of the National Assembly, said
Monday that if the government made a decision to send the forces,
as the president of legislative body, he would welcome that
decision.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie announced Sunday his
readiness to accept a peacekeeping force through the United
Nations to restore peace and security in East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Asian Economy Is Expected to Grow by 5.5 pct This year: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- With its faster than expected
recovery in the first half of 1999, the Asian economy is expected
to grow by 5.5 percent in the year, the Asian Development Bank
(ADB) predicted here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This growth rate is 1.1 percent higher than the ADB predicted
in its "Asian Development Outlook 1999" which was released in
April.
</P>
<P>
In the "Asian Development Outlook 1999 Update," the
Manila-based bank said that Asia's economic recovery in the first
half of 1999 has been stronger than expected.
</P>
<P>
"Since the first quarter of 1999, economic activity in
developing Asia has picked up substantially. This trend
strengthened further in the second quarter," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that developing Asia grew by 4.8 percent in the
first quarter, compared to 1 percent in the last quarter of 1998,
and this was further reinforced by a stronger growth performance
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The recovery from the financial crisis, which started in
mid-1997, is being led by South Korea, with 4.6 percent growth in
the first quarter, 9.8 percent for the second quarter and a
forecast 8 percent for the year, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Taipei, China; Singapore; the Philippines; and Thailand follow
South Korea in that order," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, the gross domestic product (GDP) in
Singapore is expected to increase by 5 percent this year, and in
the Philippines and Thailand 3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the faster than expected recovery in Asia in
the first half of the year has been fueled by an expansion in
domestic demand arising from reflationary policies and increased
global demand for semi-conductors and electronic products.
</P>
<P>
The winding down of Y2K-related demand for electronics in the
second half of 1999 is likely to be offset by a rise in domestic
demand, it said.
</P>
<P>
"This will, however, depend upon the continued progress in
corporate and financial sector reforms," the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
"Real GDP growth in developing Asia is expected to be 5.5
percent in 1999 and 2000. This is based on continued improvement
in domestic demand and sustained external demand and arising from
higher growth rate in world trade and expansion in intra-regional
trade," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to inflation in the region, the bank said that the
second quarter consumer price index inflation rate for developing
Asia was 0.4 percent, compared with 5.4 percent in the last
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is forecast to experience the most dramatic decline
in inflation, which may average about 2 percent in 1999 compared
with a peak of over 80 percent in September 1998, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
In India, it added, inflation fell to less than 2 percent, the
lowest in nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
There has been deflation in China, China's Hong Kong, South
Korea and Thailand, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank also said that the June figure for short-term interest
rates indicate that with a few exceptions, rates across the region
are below pre-crisis levels.
</P>
<P>
"The fall in interest rates in the crisis-affected countries
are due to improvements in the balance of payments and the relaxed
monetary policies," it said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said that central banks are expected to keep short-term
interest rates low to keep financial sector reforms on track,
avoid further currency appreciation and raise domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
"However, the short-term prospects of a recovery in private
investment remain weak," it added.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that Asia has a large agenda for structural
reform which needs to be vigorously pursued.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring the banking and corporate sectors and making
business transactions more transparent and accountable will
increase efficiency in resource allocation, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Policy initiatives are required for raising productivity
levels and restoring international competitiveness. This alone
will put developing Asia back on the path of sustained growth
which is essential for tackling poverty in the region," it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
