<HEADLINE> Venezuela Rejects Colombian Paramilitary Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan Foreign Minister
Jose Vicente Rangel Monday denounced and rejected threats made by
Colombian paramilitary militias against his country.
</P>
<P>
"We look down on them," said Rangel, when he was asked to
comment on statements made by the head of the United Auto-Defenses
of Colombia, Carlos Castano. The statements were included in a
letter sent to Victor G. Ricardo, the high commissioner for peace
in the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
"We have more important things to do than respond to threats
from a group of totally unqualified people," Rangel said, adding
that the Venezuelan government "isn't dissuaded by threats."
</P>
<P>
"We're made for fighting and prepared to face any action of any
kind, with the will power Venezuelans express during times of
conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he denied that he recently met with the
heads of the guerrilla forces -- Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia (FARC) and the National Liberation Army (ELN).
</P>
<P>
"I haven't met anyone. Until now, I have not. If a meeting is
planned, I'll be happy to hold it on Venezuelan land," said Rangel.
</P>
<P>
The leader of Colombia's right-wing militias, Carlos Castano,
Sunday accused Venezuela's air force of violating Colombian
airspace to conduct raids on his forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
