<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Deepens Commitment to Advanced Programming Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp. made a
series of announcements Monday supporting the Extensible Markup
Language (XML), a technology promised to move the Internet forward
into a whole new and more powerful era of computing.
</P>
<P>
XML, the electronic-publishing language, was completed in 1998
by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) and has spread through
science into industries ranging from manufacturing to medicine.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the Web's current main language HTML (shorthand for
hypertext markup language), which describes the structure of a Web
page, XML allows developers to make up their own tags to describe
information content on the page.
</P>
<P>
This industry-standard technology, far more flexible than HTML,
therefore enables heterogeneous interoperability of data,
components, business processes and applications over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft said in its announcements that it has actively
participated in the W3C's creation and standardization of XML, and
has delivered XML support in its products.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft Internet Explorer was the first browser software to
support XML. The windows 2000 operating system is the first
operating system with integrated XML support.
</P>
<P>
The new product the company announced Monday is Windows
Distributed Internet Architecture (Windows DNA) 2000, a
comprehensive, integrated platform for building and operating
state-of-the-art distributed Web applications as well as the next
wave of Internet-based Web services.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft said that XML is the key for its vision of integrated,
programmable Web services. Through the exchange of XML messages,
services can easily describe their capabilities and allow any
other service, application or device on the Internet to invoke
those capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that XML and applications based on the
language, in the first place, will promote electronic commerce.
Commerce has been conducted for centuries by exchanging
standardized documents, and XML was designed exactly for document
exchange.
</P>
<P>
It is becoming clear that universal electronic commerce will
rely heavily on a flow of agreements, expressed in millions of XML
documents pulsing around the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the XML-powered Web will be faster, friendlier and a
better place to do business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President, NZ Prime Minister Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China is satisfied with
the overall development of its ties with New Zealand, visiting
Chinese President Jiang Zemin said during his talks with New
Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said that New Zealand-China ties are entering into a
period of smooth progress and the ongoing visit by Jiang, the
first by a Chinese head of state, will surely serve to push
bilateral ties to a new period of promotion.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the just-concluded informal meeting of leaders of
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum has produced
positive results, she thanked Jiang for his important
contributions to the success of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Jiang congratulated Shipley on the success of the APEC meeting.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders spoke highly of the smooth development of ties
between the two countries over the past 27 years.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said current bilateral ties are enjoying a good momentum
and leaders of the two nations have maintained frequent contacts.
</P>
<P>
Not long ago, he went on to say, Shipley paid a successful
visit to China, which served to further relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
On international and regional issues, Jiang said both sides
maintain good consultations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, he noted, bilateral economic and trade
relations have developed from a purely trading relationship to a
multi-level and multifarious trade and economic cooperation in
many fields; and each country has become an important trading and
investment partner of the other.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral exchanges in the cultural, scientific,
educational and tourism fields have achieved new progress, Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the New Zealand government gives priority to its
ties with Asia in its foreign policy and values development of its
ties with China.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand is the first Western nation to reach agreement with
China on China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO),
Jiang said, adding China appreciates the positive efforts of the
New Zealand government in promoting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Although there have occurred some new changes in international
and regional situation, he said, peace and development have
remained the main theme of the times.
</P>
<P>
China and New Zealand, as two Asian-Pacific countries with
important influence, share common interests in safeguarding world
and regional peace and stability, and in maintaining regional
prosperity and development, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said the two economies are strongly complementary to each
other and there exist good basis and broad prospects for
furthering mutually beneficial friendly cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two countries, he continued, should view from a
historical height the overall circumstances of the bilateral ties,
and the long-term interests of the two peoples, and push bilateral
relations further.
</P>
<P>
Both sides vowed to make concerted efforts for the
establishment of a long-term, stable, smooth and all-round
relationship of cooperation geared toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Echoing Jiang's viewpoints on bilateral relations, Shipley said
her country treasures its ties with China.
</P>
<P>
Since establishment of diplomatic ties, Shipley went on to say,
leaders of the two nations have frequently exchanged visits, while
bilateral contacts and exchanges in various sectors have scored
continuous development and positive results, with which New
Zealand feels satisfied.
</P>
<P>
Shipley stated that her country hopes to further increase
mutual understanding and enhance ties with China, a large and
influential country in the world.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that her country firmly supports China's entry
into the WTO at an early date.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, Shipley reiterated that her government has
always followed and will continue to stick to the one-China policy.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the settlement of the Taiwan-related issue at
the APEC meeting demonstrated the New Zealand government's
determination to follow the one-China policy.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his appreciation for that and reiterated China'
s principled stance on this issue.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Jiang and Shipley jointly met with the press.
</P>
</TEXT>
