<HEADLINE> SITIC Pays Off Foreign Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- With the recent settlement of
the 134-million-U.S.dollar Singaporean floating rate notes,
Shandong International Trust and Investment Corp (SITIC has paid
off all its foreign debts over the past two years, Tuesday's China
Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
The pay-off of the 392-million-U.S.dollar foreign debts was
completed against a grim financial market, sources from the SITIC
said.
</P>
<P>
The bankruptcy of Guangdong International Trust and Investment
Corp (GITIC) last year had a negative impact on the industry, and
the opportunities for raising funds from overseas were closed for
Chinese trust companies for some time.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, SITIC has committed itself to controlling risks and
improving project management, which allowed it to pay off all
debts on time.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the foreign debt ratio of all China's state-owned
investment firms has been kept within a reasonable range," said
Wang Huisheng, secretary-general of the Investment Association of
China.
</P>
<P>
The assets of those firms total some 300 billion yuan (36.14
billion U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
Wang noted that most of the foreign debts have been used in
projects of infrastructure construction, basic industries and
pillar industries. Those projects have strong social and economic
results, which lay the foundation for the timely repayment of the
debts.
</P>
<P>
As for SITIC, its lawful and risk-controlled operations have
earned it the first position in the credit rating by Moody's among
all provincial trust companies in China for three consecutive
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
