<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firms and Presses Gain Import Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Culture
yesterday gave the go-ahead for 28 of the country's companies and
publishing houses to import and publish cultural, literary,
artistic and audio-visual products.
</P>
<P>
To be eligible, publishers had to undergo intense questioning
about their business practices, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
"All of these companies and publishing houses have registered
funds of over 2 million RMB yuan (240,960 USD) and a good
reputation in publishing domestic audio-visual products," said Tuo
Zuhai, a leading official in charge of the work.
</P>
<P>
They must also have no history of suspicious or illegal
business dealings, especially those involving copyright laws, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Included in the group are big business such as China Gramophone
Record Corporation, China Record and Videotape Publishing House,
China International Television Corporation, Beijing Audio-Visual
Company and Shanghai Audio-Visual Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
China Book Import and Export Corporation (CBIEC), which has
previously gained license to import books, is now allowed to
expand its business scope to import of completed audio-visual
products.
</P>
<P>
CBIEC and other 27 companies are the first batch to win the
import rights for audio-visual products, and the ministry expects
to approve more businesses in the future, according to Tuo.
</P>
<P>
"The examination and approval steps are key to carrying out the
Managerial Measures on the Import of Audio-Visual Products," he
explained. The measures were issued jointly by the Ministry of
Culture and the General Administration of Customs on April 30.
</P>
<P>
The measures have defined what type of companies and publishing
houses were entitled to importing and publishing foreign audio-
visual products, and when this right would be re-examined to avoid
disorder in the field, he said, adding that this marked a major
advance towards regulating the business.
</P>
<P>
China has around 112 companies and publishing houses engaged in
unlicensed import and publication of overseas audio-visual
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Hold Int'l Piano Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The second China
International Piano Competition, sponsored by China Ministry of
Culture, will be held at Beijing Concert Hall from December 2-12,
today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Among the judges will be 14 renowned pianists and music
educators from 11 countries and regions, said an official with the
ministry, including Marcello Abbado (Italy), Bao Huiqiao (China),
Hiroko Nakamura (Japan), Pnina Salzman (Israel), Fanny Waterman (
England), Karl-Heinz Kaemmerling (Germany) and Jerome Lowenthal (
USA).
</P>
<P>
The artistic director for the event will be Wu Zuqiang,
honorary president of China Central Conservatory of Music, who
served in the same capacity in the first competition, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Applicants from 50 countries and regions have applied for the
competition, he said. They were asked to send the organizing
committee a tape recording with the required repertoire: two
virtuoso etudes, including one Chopin etude; one prelude and fugue
from the "Well-tempered Clavier" By Bach; one classical sonata and
one work of the applicant's choice.
</P>
<P>
After the first round of selections, 55 participants will take
part in the final competition in Beijing. The youngest participant
is 17-year-old Li Yundi from China, and the oldest, 30-year-old
Park Chong W. from Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The first competition was held in 1995, with 45 participants
from 18 countries and regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pictures Mirror Early 20th-Century China(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gamble's photo archive was discovered by his eldest daughter
Catherine in the attic of her home in 1984. Catherine was born in
Beijing in 1926 and the discovery of the photo collection started
her on a long journey to Beijing and to the old place where her
father devoted his youth and love, she says.
</P>
<P>
She established the Sidney D. Gamble Foundation for China
studies in 1986 to preserve, catalogue, interpret, and share the
photographic legacy of her father with scholars and with the
general public.
</P>
<P>
Standing in front of the Museum of Chinese History east of the
Tiananmen Square recently, she said that her father would be
thrilled to know that so many of his photos will be seen for the
first time by thousands of Chinese and that it has been a long and
exciting journey but they have completed the circle.
</P>
<P>
It's a wise child that knows its own father, she says, and
thinks and hopes that she is the wiser now for having looked at
China through her father's eyes and through his camera lens and
that she has shared his youthful enthusiasm and joy of discovery.
</P>
<P>
She says she hopes these old photos will remind the Chinese of
the turbulent years of their country's past and help them know
their fathers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
