<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Spending in Thailand Rises in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's advertisement
industry has seen light of hope as the country's total media
spending in the first eight months of this year rose by 3.7
percent to 25.8 billion baht (678.9 million U.S. dollars) over the
same period last year, a report of Media Data Resource said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, which is available Tuesday, spending
on TV media increased by 6 percent to 17.5 billion baht (460.5
million dollars) and on radio up by 19 percent to 2.5 billion baht
(65.8 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Magazine spending rose by 7.7 percent to 1.4 billion baht (36.8
million dollars) while cinema outlays were up 18.7 percent to 127
million baht (3.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, media spending on newspapers dropped to 3.5 billion
baht (92.1 million dollars) from 3.8 billion baht (100 million
dollars) and that for outdoor advertising dipped to 675 million
baht (17.8 million dollars), down by 23.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Advertising on music cassettes and CDs led the spending, at 2.4
billion baht (63.2 million dollars), followed by corporate
advertising at 1.6 billion baht (42.1 million dollars), hair-cut
products at 1.2 billion baht (31.6 million dollars), and alcoholic
drinks at 1.1 billion baht (28.9 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
