<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Links Between Nepal, Sri Lanka Doubled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka and Nepal have
agreed to increase their airlines' operations in each other's
country, the official Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The governments of the two countries have decided to increase
the current operation frequency of two flights per week to four.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to this effect was signed in Kathmandu last week
by the civil aviation ministers of the two countries, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Sri Lankan Air Lines, the designated
carrier of Sri Lanka, will operate via Dhaka, Bangladesh, and
similarly Royal Nepal Airlines would be permitted to operate via
Male with traffic rights.
</P>
<P>
Air Lanka, which was Sri Lanka's national carrier set up in
1979, was renamed Sri Lankan Airlines in July this year in
preparation for becoming an international airline the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
A new airbus A340 has been obtained on dry lease for five years
from Airbus Industries of Europe. Sri Lankan Airlines will also
take delivery of six more airbuses beginning from October at the
cost of 540 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Airlines now flies to 26 destinations in 20
countries in Europe, the Middle East, South Asia and the Far East.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
