<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Optimistic of Peace in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
optimistic that no clashes would mar the month-long period leading
to the resumption of peace talks with the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF), a senior official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a radio interview, National Defense Secretary
Orlando Mercado said the situation in Mindanao has normalized
following the military's successful rescue operation for a
four-year-old kidnapped girl.
</P>
<P>
"We hope there would be no more clashes to delay the peace
process," Mercado noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the recent agreement reached by the government and the
MILF to resume talks on October 25 would boost the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"This can be helpful for us to be able to start the process. In
the meantime, things have normalized as far as the situation in
Mindanao is concerned," he added.
</P>
<P>
Last month, government troops killed several rebels during the
rescue operation in Basilan for four-year-old girl Wilmarie
Furigay.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada said this shows the
government is in control over Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Also, the president has vowed to take steps to end official
neglect of the development of Mindanao in the past decades and
transform it into the country's food basket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Stresses Humanitarian Crisis in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The grave humanitarian
crisis in East Timor should be given the topmost priority by the
United Nations, according to a five-member Security Council
delegation Monday.
</P>
<P>
The team, which just returned from Indonesia, proposed that a
council resolution be adopted to provide a framework for deploying
a U.N.-sponsored international force to cooperate with it in
restoring security in East Timor, as accepted by Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Due to security concerns, the delegation suggested that the
United Nations Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) reduce to a minimum
or evacuate its personnel in East Timor's capital of Dili before
the arrival of an international security presence.
</P>
<P>
During its five-day stay in Indonesia, the ambassadorial
delegation led by Namibian Permanent Representative to the U.N.
Martin Andjaba, met high-ranking government officials and visited
East Timor, conveying U.N.'s concerns about the deteriorating
security conditions in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
In the U.N., Secretary-General Kofi Annan appointed Monday U.N.
Assistant Emergency Relief Coordinator Ross Mountain as U.N.
Humanitarian Coordinator for the East Timor Crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council met Monday on the dispatch of the
international force to East Timor soon after Annan met
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990914.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wellington's Official Ceremony in Honor of President Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Governor-
General Sir Micheal Hardie Boys held an official ceremony here
Tuesday to warmly welcome visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, here on a state visit, is the first head of state of
China to visit New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The welcome ceremony was held on the front lawn of the
Government House. When President Jiang and his wife, Wang Yeping,
arrived at the Government House, they were greeted by Governor-
General Boys and his wife.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, after a traditional Maori's welcome dance, the
New Zealand military band played the National Anthems of the
People's Republic of China and New Zealand amidst a 21-gun salute.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley and Chinese Vice-
Premier Qian Qichen attended the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
