<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, September 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Monday hoped the U.N.
Security Council would Rapidly authorize a multinational
peacekeeping force for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"What we have indicated is that we would like delegates in New
York to move rapidly on a fast track to pass a resolution
authorizing a multinational force to move to East Timor to provide
security and restore order," State Department spokesman James
Rubin said. (US-E.Timor)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Widespread floods caused by a week of torrential
rains have rendered 9,195 people homeless in upper east and
northern regions of Ghana, and an accompanying cholera outbreak
has killed at least 48 people in these regions, the Ghana News
Agency reported Monday. (Ghana-Floods)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank on Monday called on African
leaders, the private sector, and society at large to push the HIV/
AIDS crisis in Sub-Saharan Africa to the center of their national
agendas in order to stop the fastest-growing threat to development
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Nowhere in the world has the impact of HIV/AIDS been more
severe than in Sub-Saharan Africa, the World Bank said. (World
Bank-Africa-AIDS)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet, who is
currently under house arrest in London, was taken to hospital on
Monday for a brain scan.
</P>
<P>
The 83-year-old general was under close observation, his
spokesman told reporters. But no further details of Pinochet's
health condition was given. (Britain-Pinochet)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Northern Ireland's leading Protestant party on Monday
rejected the proposals to reform the British province's police
force and said it would draw up alternative ideas.
</P>
<P>
After a three-hour meeting, the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP)
described the report by an independent commission headed by Chris
Patten as "deeply flawed and objectionable". (N.Ireland-Unionists)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on
Monday that the responsibility for the protection of civilians in
armed conflict cannot be transferred to others and the United
Nations is the only international organization with the reach and
authority to fulfill this task. (Annan-Recommendations) 
</P>
