<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council met on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council met Monday on East Timor with no further
announcements on the dispatch of an international peace-keeping
force to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
After two hours of closed-door consultations, council
president, Peter van Walsum of the Netherlands said council
members welcome Indonesian President B.J. Habibie's readiness to
accept the force to restore order in the territory.
</P>
<P>
That is what he can tell the press as the mandate of the force
had not been nailed down, Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
Ruling out significant differences among the 15 council members
over the mandate of the force, he said it needs fine-tuning.
</P>
<P>
The discussions followed the meeting of U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan with Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas soon after
the latter's arrival in New York.
</P>
<P>
Alatas was sent by President Habibie to discuss the details of
the U.N. proposal of sending such a force.
</P>
<P>
Both Annan and Alatas agreed that the move is an important step
in restoring peace and security in East Timor and the parties
should move ahead as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
"The Foreign Minister raised no conditions to the deployment of
a U.N.-authorized force," said Annan.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief expressed his hope that with the Foreign
Ministers of Portugal and Australia now en route to New York, "the
details will be worked out in the next 24 hours or so".
</P>
<P>
Alatas said his talks with Annan will continue Tuesday on a
number of issues including the composition and the nature of the
force and the role of the Indonesian army in the peace-keeping
mission, and that he is open-minded towards the force's make-up.
</P>
<P>
Before attending the council meeting, Chinese Permanent
Representative to the U.N. Qin Huasun said China hopes that the
international community will fully take into account the
complexity and sensibility of the East Timor issue in terms of the
composition of the peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
China would like to see the international community to take a
positive approach towards the concrete requests raised by
Indonesia in this regard, he said.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes Indonesia's decision to invite the international
force, seeing it a very positive development, Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's decision is a show of its sincerity of carrying out
its commitment to keeping peace and security in East Timor during
its transition to independence, Qin said, adding that China hopes
the international action will be constructive to a quick
restoration of security in East Timor. (cv)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
